WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.960 align:middle line:90%


00:00:04.960 --> 00:00:07.936 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:07.936 --> 00:00:20.878 align:middle line:90%


00:00:20.878 --> 00:00:22.420 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA GARR: You've
heard the phrase,

00:00:22.420 --> 00:00:24.650 align:middle line:90%
"To be human is to suffer."

00:00:24.650 --> 00:00:28.660 align:middle line:84%
Yet, the Dalai Lama has a
mission to end suffering.

00:00:28.660 --> 00:00:31.480 align:middle line:84%
So is suffering really
necessary for the soul

00:00:31.480 --> 00:00:34.210 align:middle line:90%
to grow and to find meaning?

00:00:34.210 --> 00:00:35.770 align:middle line:84%
Hi, I'm Lisa Garr,
and joining me

00:00:35.770 --> 00:00:39.310 align:middle line:84%
is a senior rabbi at Wilshire
Boulevard Temple, Rabbi Steve

00:00:39.310 --> 00:00:43.210 align:middle line:84%
Leder, who was twice named by
Newsweek as one of the 10 most

00:00:43.210 --> 00:00:45.610 align:middle line:90%
influential rabbis in America.

00:00:45.610 --> 00:00:48.190 align:middle line:10%
In his book "More
Beautiful Than Before,"

00:00:48.190 --> 00:00:51.640 align:middle line:10%
Rabbi Leder talks about his own
journey with pain and suffering

00:00:51.640 --> 00:00:54.040 align:middle line:10%
and how it made him
more available than ever

00:00:54.040 --> 00:00:57.020 align:middle line:10%
before to listen to
people's stories about pain.

00:00:57.020 --> 00:00:57.820 align:middle line:10%
Welcome.

00:00:57.820 --> 00:00:58.380 align:middle line:10%
>>STEVE LEDER: Thank you.

00:00:58.380 --> 00:00:59.547 align:middle line:10%
I'm very honored to be here.

00:00:59.547 --> 00:01:01.660 align:middle line:10%
>>LISA: No, it's my pleasure.

00:01:01.660 --> 00:01:04.970 align:middle line:10%
You do hear a lot of people's
stories about pain, don't you?

00:01:04.970 --> 00:01:05.770 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: I do.

00:01:05.770 --> 00:01:08.410 align:middle line:10%
Listen, I'm the
senior rabbi of one

00:01:08.410 --> 00:01:10.240 align:middle line:10%
of the largest
synagogues in the world.

00:01:10.240 --> 00:01:10.570 align:middle line:10%
I'm--

00:01:10.570 --> 00:01:11.500 align:middle line:10%
>>LISA: Wow.

00:01:11.500 --> 00:01:12.875 align:middle line:10%
>>LEDER: --ultimately
responsible

00:01:12.875 --> 00:01:16.270 align:middle line:10%
for about 10,000
people's religious lives.

00:01:16.270 --> 00:01:18.400 align:middle line:84%
And therefore,
it's my phone that

00:01:18.400 --> 00:01:20.590 align:middle line:84%
rings when people's
lives fall apart,

00:01:20.590 --> 00:01:23.140 align:middle line:84%
when their bodies fall
apart, when they're facing

00:01:23.140 --> 00:01:27.430 align:middle line:90%
the scalpel or the cemetery.

00:01:27.430 --> 00:01:31.400 align:middle line:10%
And this happens many hundreds
of times over my more than 30

00:01:31.400 --> 00:01:32.200 align:middle line:10%
years there.

00:01:32.200 --> 00:01:35.950 align:middle line:10%
So I've been on the inside
of an awful lot of suffering.

00:01:35.950 --> 00:01:38.080 align:middle line:84%
The way a friend of mine
puts it is he said, Steve,

00:01:38.080 --> 00:01:40.800 align:middle line:84%
your job is a
front-row seat to life.

00:01:40.800 --> 00:01:41.900 align:middle line:90%
And that's true.

00:01:41.900 --> 00:01:42.700 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes.

00:01:42.700 --> 00:01:44.750 align:middle line:90%
Does it ever wear on you?

00:01:44.750 --> 00:01:45.790 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: Oh, it does.

00:01:45.790 --> 00:01:47.320 align:middle line:90%
It does.

00:01:47.320 --> 00:01:51.190 align:middle line:84%
You know, cliches become
cliches because they're

00:01:51.190 --> 00:01:52.840 align:middle line:90%
fundamentally true.

00:01:52.840 --> 00:01:57.230 align:middle line:84%
And we've all heard of this
notion of the wounded healer.

00:01:57.230 --> 00:02:02.950 align:middle line:84%
I don't think it would be
possible to serve and to be

00:02:02.950 --> 00:02:07.150 align:middle line:84%
in giving mode and
in caretaking mode

00:02:07.150 --> 00:02:09.250 align:middle line:84%
for that many years
and that many hours

00:02:09.250 --> 00:02:11.910 align:middle line:84%
and that many days
and weeks and months

00:02:11.910 --> 00:02:16.330 align:middle line:84%
for decades without
being depleted by it.

00:02:16.330 --> 00:02:21.940 align:middle line:84%
The hope is that you can be
secure in your own spirituality

00:02:21.940 --> 00:02:25.330 align:middle line:84%
and your own sense of
meaning and that it's

00:02:25.330 --> 00:02:28.150 align:middle line:84%
worth the sacrifice to
you, without denying

00:02:28.150 --> 00:02:31.760 align:middle line:84%
the fact that it is a
tremendous sacrifice.

00:02:31.760 --> 00:02:32.560 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes.

00:02:32.560 --> 00:02:33.977 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: But
hopefully, one you're

00:02:33.977 --> 00:02:36.610 align:middle line:84%
proud of having
made with your life.

00:02:36.610 --> 00:02:39.610 align:middle line:84%
But no, it's not an
easy road to travel.

00:02:39.610 --> 00:02:41.920 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: You've seen
generation upon generation

00:02:41.920 --> 00:02:43.830 align:middle line:84%
come through your
congregation, haven't you?

00:02:43.830 --> 00:02:44.350 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: Yes.

00:02:44.350 --> 00:02:45.150 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:02:45.150 --> 00:02:49.810 align:middle line:84%
I've been there long enough
now to be doing Bar and Bat

00:02:49.810 --> 00:02:51.610 align:middle line:84%
Mitzvahs for the
children of couples

00:02:51.610 --> 00:02:54.970 align:middle line:84%
I married, to be
burying grandparents

00:02:54.970 --> 00:02:59.770 align:middle line:84%
and parents of a child,
to be doing weddings

00:02:59.770 --> 00:03:02.750 align:middle line:84%
of the children of
people I married,

00:03:02.750 --> 00:03:05.500 align:middle line:90%
which is quite extraordinary.

00:03:05.500 --> 00:03:07.125 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: You wonder
where the time goes.

00:03:07.125 --> 00:03:07.925 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: Yes.

00:03:07.925 --> 00:03:08.767 align:middle line:90%
Yes, for all of us.

00:03:08.767 --> 00:03:10.600 align:middle line:84%
I think my mother had
this expression, which

00:03:10.600 --> 00:03:13.370 align:middle line:84%
is so true, which I didn't
understand when I was young.

00:03:13.370 --> 00:03:16.220 align:middle line:84%
She would say, the days are
long, but the years are short.

00:03:16.220 --> 00:03:17.020 align:middle line:90%
It's very true.

00:03:17.020 --> 00:03:18.640 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes, absolutely.

00:03:18.640 --> 00:03:21.310 align:middle line:84%
And then you had your own
experience with pain recently.

00:03:21.310 --> 00:03:22.185 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: Well, I did.

00:03:22.185 --> 00:03:24.790 align:middle line:84%
So we were just talking about
the extraordinary amount

00:03:24.790 --> 00:03:26.950 align:middle line:84%
of pain that I've
witnessed and tried

00:03:26.950 --> 00:03:28.990 align:middle line:90%
to help people walk through.

00:03:28.990 --> 00:03:32.470 align:middle line:84%
And then I had my own
experience with severe pain.

00:03:32.470 --> 00:03:35.320 align:middle line:84%
About five years ago now, I
had a very frightening car

00:03:35.320 --> 00:03:39.220 align:middle line:84%
accident-- a hit
and run, by the way.

00:03:39.220 --> 00:03:41.950 align:middle line:84%
It was a large SUV and
turned our car around.

00:03:41.950 --> 00:03:44.710 align:middle line:90%
The airbags went off.

00:03:44.710 --> 00:03:47.170 align:middle line:84%
And I thought that,
physically, I had walked away

00:03:47.170 --> 00:03:49.860 align:middle line:90%
from it relatively unscathed--

00:03:49.860 --> 00:03:53.050 align:middle line:84%
a little scraped up,
but nothing more.

00:03:53.050 --> 00:03:55.390 align:middle line:10%
And then, a few
months later, I had

00:03:55.390 --> 00:04:03.820 align:middle line:10%
this extraordinarily painful,
torturous lower back pain

00:04:03.820 --> 00:04:08.680 align:middle line:10%
that shot down to my left toes
and essentially, honestly,

00:04:08.680 --> 00:04:09.643 align:middle line:10%
left me paralyzed.

00:04:09.643 --> 00:04:11.060 align:middle line:84%
It was the first
time in my life--

00:04:11.060 --> 00:04:13.393 align:middle line:84%
I don't know, Lisa, if you've
ever had this experience--

00:04:13.393 --> 00:04:18.265 align:middle line:84%
where my brain told my body
to move, and it wouldn't.

00:04:18.265 --> 00:04:19.390 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: That's frightening.

00:04:19.390 --> 00:04:21.557 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: Imagine your brain
saying to you, you know,

00:04:21.557 --> 00:04:24.060 align:middle line:84%
scratch this itch, and
your arm just doesn't move.

00:04:24.060 --> 00:04:26.620 align:middle line:84%
Well, my brain said, walk,
and I just couldn't move.

00:04:26.620 --> 00:04:28.480 align:middle line:90%
It was just too painful.

00:04:28.480 --> 00:04:36.190 align:middle line:84%
And this led to opioids,
steroids, surgery,

00:04:36.190 --> 00:04:43.240 align:middle line:84%
more opioids, more steroids,
opioid addiction, depression,

00:04:43.240 --> 00:04:46.060 align:middle line:84%
a downward spiral
that was pretty awful.

00:04:46.060 --> 00:04:48.160 align:middle line:90%
And I came out of it.

00:04:48.160 --> 00:04:51.860 align:middle line:84%
I came out of it for a
lot of different reasons.

00:04:51.860 --> 00:04:54.700 align:middle line:84%
And those reasons
formed the foundation

00:04:54.700 --> 00:04:56.540 align:middle line:84%
of this book, "More
Beautiful Than Before--

00:04:56.540 --> 00:04:58.420 align:middle line:90%
How Suffering Transforms Us."

00:04:58.420 --> 00:05:02.290 align:middle line:84%
And in a way, the
book is, in a way,

00:05:02.290 --> 00:05:05.260 align:middle line:90%
my apology to my congregation.

00:05:05.260 --> 00:05:08.140 align:middle line:84%
Because for 27 years
before this accident,

00:05:08.140 --> 00:05:10.360 align:middle line:84%
I was talking to
people about pain

00:05:10.360 --> 00:05:12.410 align:middle line:84%
and trying to help them
through their pain.

00:05:12.410 --> 00:05:14.860 align:middle line:84%
And I realized, after this
accident and this surgery

00:05:14.860 --> 00:05:18.160 align:middle line:84%
and this depression,
that despite my best

00:05:18.160 --> 00:05:23.670 align:middle line:84%
efforts in the past, I actually
knew almost nothing about pain.

00:05:23.670 --> 00:05:26.610 align:middle line:84%
And I wanted to set
the record straight.

00:05:26.610 --> 00:05:31.330 align:middle line:84%
So while the book is only maybe
5% about me and my situation,

00:05:31.330 --> 00:05:35.250 align:middle line:84%
it is 100% about
how can each of us

00:05:35.250 --> 00:05:38.160 align:middle line:84%
journey through pain, which
is inevitable for all of us.

00:05:38.160 --> 00:05:42.270 align:middle line:84%
How can we journey
through it in a way that

00:05:42.270 --> 00:05:44.120 align:middle line:90%
makes our lives more worthy?

00:05:44.120 --> 00:05:48.180 align:middle line:84%
You know, Dostoyevsky
said his greatest fear

00:05:48.180 --> 00:05:52.140 align:middle line:84%
was that his life would not
be worthy of his suffering.

00:05:52.140 --> 00:05:53.320 align:middle line:90%
That's such a powerful idea.

00:05:53.320 --> 00:05:54.120 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: It is.

00:05:54.120 --> 00:05:57.510 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: Can you be
worthy of your pain?

00:05:57.510 --> 00:06:01.230 align:middle line:84%
Can your life be worthy of
what you have been through?

00:06:01.230 --> 00:06:03.180 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: The enormous
amount of suffering

00:06:03.180 --> 00:06:06.240 align:middle line:84%
that the Jewish people
have gone through,

00:06:06.240 --> 00:06:11.380 align:middle line:84%
and to make their lives worthy
of the history of the pain.

00:06:11.380 --> 00:06:12.180 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: Yes.

00:06:12.180 --> 00:06:13.920 align:middle line:84%
I've given that
sermon many times.

00:06:13.920 --> 00:06:18.537 align:middle line:84%
You know, what will we, the
luckiest Jews who ever lived--

00:06:18.537 --> 00:06:19.620 align:middle line:90%
by the way, which is true.

00:06:19.620 --> 00:06:20.620 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: To be alive now.

00:06:20.620 --> 00:06:23.010 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: To be alive
now, in this hemisphere,

00:06:23.010 --> 00:06:29.130 align:middle line:84%
in this country is unprecedented
freedom and strength

00:06:29.130 --> 00:06:31.290 align:middle line:84%
and support for
Jews and Judaism.

00:06:31.290 --> 00:06:33.960 align:middle line:84%
And I often ask
myself every day,

00:06:33.960 --> 00:06:36.630 align:middle line:84%
and my congregation,
what will we,

00:06:36.630 --> 00:06:38.520 align:middle line:84%
the luckiest Jews
who ever lived,

00:06:38.520 --> 00:06:40.080 align:middle line:90%
do with our good fortune?

00:06:40.080 --> 00:06:41.670 align:middle line:90%
Will we squander it?

00:06:41.670 --> 00:06:43.500 align:middle line:90%
Will we disappear?

00:06:43.500 --> 00:06:47.880 align:middle line:84%
Or will we honor the sacrifices
of those who came before us

00:06:47.880 --> 00:06:50.620 align:middle line:84%
and make the most
of this opportunity?

00:06:50.620 --> 00:06:52.680 align:middle line:90%
And this is on a macro level.

00:06:52.680 --> 00:06:54.540 align:middle line:84%
But of course, also,
you're quite right.

00:06:54.540 --> 00:06:58.470 align:middle line:84%
On a more micro
level, what will we

00:06:58.470 --> 00:07:02.400 align:middle line:84%
do with our lives, given
the suffering we've endured

00:07:02.400 --> 00:07:04.470 align:middle line:84%
and that others
have endured for us?

00:07:04.470 --> 00:07:07.410 align:middle line:90%
What will we make of our lives?

00:07:07.410 --> 00:07:08.970 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: And it's for all people.

00:07:08.970 --> 00:07:11.190 align:middle line:84%
Think about all the
suffering that's gone on.

00:07:11.190 --> 00:07:14.310 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: It is the common
denominator to being human.

00:07:14.310 --> 00:07:17.290 align:middle line:90%
All humans suffer pain.

00:07:17.290 --> 00:07:18.090 align:middle line:90%
All of us.

00:07:18.090 --> 00:07:21.330 align:middle line:84%
There is no way to get
through life without it.

00:07:21.330 --> 00:07:24.190 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: But it makes us grow,
and it makes us who we are.

00:07:24.190 --> 00:07:25.942 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: It can.

00:07:25.942 --> 00:07:27.150 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: You're right, it can.

00:07:27.150 --> 00:07:27.570 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: Right.

00:07:27.570 --> 00:07:28.210 align:middle line:90%
It can.

00:07:28.210 --> 00:07:29.585 align:middle line:84%
And that's the
point of the book,

00:07:29.585 --> 00:07:35.893 align:middle line:84%
is can you be worthy of this and
can you make something of it?

00:07:35.893 --> 00:07:37.560 align:middle line:84%
And I want to be clear
about something--

00:07:37.560 --> 00:07:40.770 align:middle line:84%
neither what I stand for nor
what the book articulates is,

00:07:40.770 --> 00:07:44.010 align:middle line:84%
in any way, an
idealization of suffering,

00:07:44.010 --> 00:07:45.480 align:middle line:90%
a glorification of suffering.

00:07:45.480 --> 00:07:47.160 align:middle line:90%
Suffering is terrible.

00:07:47.160 --> 00:07:48.360 align:middle line:90%
Suffering is suffering.

00:07:48.360 --> 00:07:49.260 align:middle line:90%
Pain is pain.

00:07:49.260 --> 00:07:51.210 align:middle line:84%
There's nothing good
to say about it.

00:07:51.210 --> 00:07:55.230 align:middle line:84%
However, while none of the
insights or growth that

00:07:55.230 --> 00:07:58.170 align:middle line:84%
result from pain are
worth it, I would never

00:07:58.170 --> 00:08:01.110 align:middle line:84%
say to the parents
of a child who died,

00:08:01.110 --> 00:08:02.670 align:middle line:84%
it's going to be
worth it for the way

00:08:02.670 --> 00:08:04.337 align:middle line:84%
that it informs your
life going forward.

00:08:04.337 --> 00:08:08.590 align:middle line:90%
No, it's not worth it.

00:08:08.590 --> 00:08:11.620 align:middle line:90%
But neither is it worthless.

00:08:11.620 --> 00:08:12.420 align:middle line:90%
Right?

00:08:12.420 --> 00:08:18.030 align:middle line:84%
You know, if you think about
the scroll Book of Ecclesiastes,

00:08:18.030 --> 00:08:20.810 align:middle line:84%
it says there's a
season for everything.

00:08:20.810 --> 00:08:22.837 align:middle line:90%
There's a time for everything.

00:08:22.837 --> 00:08:25.170 align:middle line:84%
And then it goes on to say
there's a time for everything

00:08:25.170 --> 00:08:26.830 align:middle line:90%
and a purpose.

00:08:26.830 --> 00:08:29.160 align:middle line:90%
It doesn't say there's a reason.

00:08:29.160 --> 00:08:30.870 align:middle line:90%
It says there's a purpose.

00:08:30.870 --> 00:08:33.299 align:middle line:84%
There is some
purpose to be found.

00:08:33.299 --> 00:08:34.710 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: That's a big difference.

00:08:34.710 --> 00:08:35.620 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: It's a huge difference.

00:08:35.620 --> 00:08:37.059 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Huge difference, because
we always look for the reason,

00:08:37.059 --> 00:08:37.859 align:middle line:90%
the meaning--

00:08:37.859 --> 00:08:41.220 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: Not trying to
pretend that suffering is just

00:08:41.220 --> 00:08:43.710 align:middle line:84%
some beautiful step on the
path toward enlightenment.

00:08:43.710 --> 00:08:44.550 align:middle line:90%
No, it's not.

00:08:44.550 --> 00:08:46.080 align:middle line:90%
It's suffering.

00:08:46.080 --> 00:08:49.230 align:middle line:84%
But there is worth
and value in it.

00:08:49.230 --> 00:08:53.850 align:middle line:10%
And I can only tell you that,
personally, what I went through

00:08:53.850 --> 00:08:59.980 align:middle line:10%
has resulted in me becoming
a more enlightened, kinder,

00:08:59.980 --> 00:09:04.470 align:middle line:10%
gentler, wiser,
better human being.

00:09:04.470 --> 00:09:06.220 align:middle line:84%
And I still wish it
hadn't happened to me.

00:09:06.220 --> 00:09:07.021 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right.

00:09:07.021 --> 00:09:08.760 align:middle line:84%
But you can also
use that as being

00:09:08.760 --> 00:09:10.800 align:middle line:90%
an example for other people.

00:09:10.800 --> 00:09:12.990 align:middle line:84%
There's so much I
want to ask you.

00:09:12.990 --> 00:09:14.260 align:middle line:90%
The opioid epidemic.

00:09:14.260 --> 00:09:15.060 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: Yes.

00:09:15.060 --> 00:09:17.460 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So you have these
young people, or all people,

00:09:17.460 --> 00:09:21.180 align:middle line:84%
who are addicted to this very
powerful substance that's

00:09:21.180 --> 00:09:25.080 align:middle line:84%
become increasingly an
epidemic amongst people.

00:09:25.080 --> 00:09:26.730 align:middle line:84%
In that place of
not knowing what

00:09:26.730 --> 00:09:29.640 align:middle line:84%
to do with the pain and
that sense of whatever it

00:09:29.640 --> 00:09:30.630 align:middle line:90%
gives you--

00:09:30.630 --> 00:09:34.260 align:middle line:84%
alleviation from the pain or
flying or whatever it is--

00:09:34.260 --> 00:09:36.510 align:middle line:90%
it helps you escape.

00:09:36.510 --> 00:09:38.340 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: Well, here's
the truth that I

00:09:38.340 --> 00:09:41.210 align:middle line:84%
don't think people
want to talk about,

00:09:41.210 --> 00:09:42.510 align:middle line:90%
and doctors particularly.

00:09:42.510 --> 00:09:45.510 align:middle line:84%
But if you get them to be
honest with you, they will.

00:09:45.510 --> 00:09:50.400 align:middle line:84%
There are certain conditions,
certain physical conditions,

00:09:50.400 --> 00:09:54.450 align:middle line:84%
for which they simply
have no better answer.

00:09:54.450 --> 00:09:55.590 align:middle line:90%
It is the only thing.

00:09:55.590 --> 00:10:00.540 align:middle line:84%
When I was curled up on the
floor like a fetus begging

00:10:00.540 --> 00:10:04.590 align:middle line:84%
for morphine, there
really was nothing else

00:10:04.590 --> 00:10:08.100 align:middle line:84%
that would have enabled me
to be in any state other

00:10:08.100 --> 00:10:10.080 align:middle line:90%
than screaming out loud.

00:10:10.080 --> 00:10:10.920 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Wow.

00:10:10.920 --> 00:10:13.020 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: So the
fact of the matter

00:10:13.020 --> 00:10:15.083 align:middle line:90%
is they're necessary sometimes.

00:10:15.083 --> 00:10:16.500 align:middle line:84%
And that's something
people really

00:10:16.500 --> 00:10:17.542 align:middle line:90%
don't want to talk about.

00:10:17.542 --> 00:10:19.190 align:middle line:90%
This is a necessary evil.

00:10:19.190 --> 00:10:22.130 align:middle line:84%
The question is, how quickly
can we transition people off

00:10:22.130 --> 00:10:24.450 align:middle line:90%
of the necessary evil?

00:10:24.450 --> 00:10:27.050 align:middle line:84%
And how can we educate
people to become more aware

00:10:27.050 --> 00:10:29.120 align:middle line:90%
of their dependency?

00:10:29.120 --> 00:10:31.672 align:middle line:90%
I slipped into the dependency.

00:10:31.672 --> 00:10:32.630 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Most people do.

00:10:32.630 --> 00:10:33.050 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: Yes.

00:10:33.050 --> 00:10:34.050 align:middle line:90%
It snuck up on me.

00:10:34.050 --> 00:10:34.850 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes.

00:10:34.850 --> 00:10:37.790 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: And I remember one
of my doctors calling me.

00:10:37.790 --> 00:10:40.098 align:middle line:90%
He called me every day.

00:10:40.098 --> 00:10:41.390 align:middle line:90%
And he said, how are you doing?

00:10:41.390 --> 00:10:43.220 align:middle line:84%
And I explained how
I was feeling to him,

00:10:43.220 --> 00:10:45.620 align:middle line:84%
and I couldn't
understand this feeling.

00:10:45.620 --> 00:10:48.130 align:middle line:84%
And he said to me,
well, you're depressed.

00:10:48.130 --> 00:10:49.910 align:middle line:10%
Now, I had never been
a depressed person

00:10:49.910 --> 00:10:51.800 align:middle line:10%
before in my life.

00:10:51.800 --> 00:10:55.370 align:middle line:84%
And I didn't have a word
for how I was feeling.

00:10:55.370 --> 00:11:00.020 align:middle line:84%
It was dark, and it was
heavy, and I had no enthusiasm

00:11:00.020 --> 00:11:01.550 align:middle line:90%
or interest in life itself.

00:11:01.550 --> 00:11:03.200 align:middle line:90%
I wasn't suicidal.

00:11:03.200 --> 00:11:05.070 align:middle line:90%
I was disinterested.

00:11:05.070 --> 00:11:05.870 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Apathetic.

00:11:05.870 --> 00:11:06.670 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: Yes.

00:11:06.670 --> 00:11:07.940 align:middle line:90%
I wanted nothing.

00:11:07.940 --> 00:11:10.010 align:middle line:84%
If you had come to me
at that point in my life

00:11:10.010 --> 00:11:13.890 align:middle line:84%
and said, Rabbi, I
have magical powers.

00:11:13.890 --> 00:11:16.400 align:middle line:84%
I can grant you any
wish, anything you want--

00:11:16.400 --> 00:11:19.950 align:middle line:84%
cure for cancer, world
peace, you name it.

00:11:19.950 --> 00:11:24.000 align:middle line:84%
I would have said, Lisa,
just leave me alone.

00:11:24.000 --> 00:11:25.220 align:middle line:90%
Just go away.

00:11:25.220 --> 00:11:27.230 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Wow.

00:11:27.230 --> 00:11:29.780 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: I wasn't
educated enough to know.

00:11:29.780 --> 00:11:32.040 align:middle line:84%
I wasn't well educated
about these opioids.

00:11:32.040 --> 00:11:34.760 align:middle line:84%
I didn't know enough
to know that it was

00:11:34.760 --> 00:11:36.500 align:middle line:90%
the opioids doing the talking.

00:11:36.500 --> 00:11:37.612 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: My goodness.

00:11:37.612 --> 00:11:40.070 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: So I think some of
this is about educating people.

00:11:40.070 --> 00:11:42.420 align:middle line:84%
Some of this is about
doctors being more careful.

00:11:42.420 --> 00:11:45.330 align:middle line:84%
Some of this is about better
research in pain management

00:11:45.330 --> 00:11:47.220 align:middle line:90%
so that we have better tools.

00:11:47.220 --> 00:11:50.870 align:middle line:84%
But this is not a problem that
is going to go away quickly.

00:11:50.870 --> 00:11:53.360 align:middle line:84%
When you have that kind
of terrible physical pain,

00:11:53.360 --> 00:11:57.210 align:middle line:84%
you will take anything
to make it better.

00:11:57.210 --> 00:11:59.150 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Well, your
book is about being

00:11:59.150 --> 00:12:02.750 align:middle line:84%
more beautiful than you were
before by being transformed

00:12:02.750 --> 00:12:03.550 align:middle line:90%
by suffering.

00:12:03.550 --> 00:12:06.440 align:middle line:84%
But the suffering
itself, wouldn't you

00:12:06.440 --> 00:12:10.220 align:middle line:90%
say, begets more suffering?

00:12:10.220 --> 00:12:12.650 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: To a point.

00:12:12.650 --> 00:12:15.450 align:middle line:90%
To a point.

00:12:15.450 --> 00:12:18.110 align:middle line:84%
But you can, and most
people do, achieve

00:12:18.110 --> 00:12:24.110 align:middle line:84%
a degree of brokenness
that gives them no choice

00:12:24.110 --> 00:12:29.120 align:middle line:84%
but to reach out for help and
to begin this road to recovery.

00:12:29.120 --> 00:12:31.860 align:middle line:84%
So it's true that pain begets
pain begets pain begets pain--

00:12:31.860 --> 00:12:32.660 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right, yes.

00:12:32.660 --> 00:12:36.500 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: --until you
are in so much pain

00:12:36.500 --> 00:12:39.170 align:middle line:84%
that you are willing to
make some kind of change

00:12:39.170 --> 00:12:40.520 align:middle line:90%
in your life, right?

00:12:40.520 --> 00:12:41.320 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes.

00:12:41.320 --> 00:12:42.382 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:12:42.382 --> 00:12:45.200 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: The Talmud says,
if you are visited by pain,

00:12:45.200 --> 00:12:48.260 align:middle line:90%
examine your life.

00:12:48.260 --> 00:12:49.880 align:middle line:84%
Now, it takes an
awful lot of pain

00:12:49.880 --> 00:12:52.945 align:middle line:84%
to make people examine
their lives, right?

00:12:52.945 --> 00:12:53.820 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: It does, yes.

00:12:53.820 --> 00:12:54.980 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: And it's
the only teacher.

00:12:54.980 --> 00:12:56.900 align:middle line:84%
You know, success doesn't
teach us anything.

00:12:56.900 --> 00:12:59.515 align:middle line:84%
All success teaches us is to
keep doing more of the same.

00:12:59.515 --> 00:13:00.315 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: True.

00:13:00.315 --> 00:13:02.107 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, it doesn't tell
you to stop anything.

00:13:02.107 --> 00:13:06.770 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: It's pain that
disrupts us and forces

00:13:06.770 --> 00:13:09.390 align:middle line:90%
us to examine our lives.

00:13:09.390 --> 00:13:11.210 align:middle line:84%
You know, Marshall
McLuhan said, I

00:13:11.210 --> 00:13:14.830 align:middle line:84%
don't know who discovered
water, but it wasn't the fish.

00:13:14.830 --> 00:13:16.580 align:middle line:84%
What he means, of
course, is that we're so

00:13:16.580 --> 00:13:19.190 align:middle line:84%
immersed in our own
reality that we're not

00:13:19.190 --> 00:13:21.290 align:middle line:90%
even aware of our own reality.

00:13:21.290 --> 00:13:23.820 align:middle line:90%
When does a fish discover water?

00:13:23.820 --> 00:13:25.530 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Never.

00:13:25.530 --> 00:13:26.943 align:middle line:84%
Oh, until they're
out of it, yes.

00:13:26.943 --> 00:13:28.985 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: When it's wriggling
on the end of a hook

00:13:28.985 --> 00:13:30.242 align:middle line:90%
and gasping and flailing.

00:13:30.242 --> 00:13:31.700 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Outside of
the water, yeah.

00:13:31.700 --> 00:13:33.533 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: That's when a
fish discovers water.

00:13:33.533 --> 00:13:35.480 align:middle line:90%
When do we discover good health?

00:13:35.480 --> 00:13:36.530 align:middle line:90%
When we lose it.

00:13:36.530 --> 00:13:40.160 align:middle line:10%
When do we discover the depth
of our love for another person?

00:13:40.160 --> 00:13:42.500 align:middle line:90%
When we lose that person, right?

00:13:42.500 --> 00:13:48.470 align:middle line:84%
So it takes that kind
of blunt force trauma

00:13:48.470 --> 00:13:54.860 align:middle line:84%
to force us, really, to think
about changing our lives.

00:13:54.860 --> 00:14:01.748 align:middle line:84%
And these changes, I posit,
it's these fundamental shifts

00:14:01.748 --> 00:14:04.040 align:middle line:84%
in our thinking and in the
way we behave and in the way

00:14:04.040 --> 00:14:06.920 align:middle line:84%
we treat others who
are also suffering,

00:14:06.920 --> 00:14:09.710 align:middle line:84%
these fundamental
changes do result

00:14:09.710 --> 00:14:11.052 align:middle line:90%
in a more beautiful life.

00:14:11.052 --> 00:14:12.260 align:middle line:90%
I'll tell you one more thing.

00:14:12.260 --> 00:14:13.420 align:middle line:90%
I know I'm rambling too long.

00:14:13.420 --> 00:14:13.690 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: No, it's OK.

00:14:13.690 --> 00:14:14.250 align:middle line:90%
Go ahead.

00:14:14.250 --> 00:14:15.667 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: This will
make the point,

00:14:15.667 --> 00:14:18.470 align:middle line:90%
I think, better than anything.

00:14:18.470 --> 00:14:20.660 align:middle line:84%
There is a verse
in the Bible that

00:14:20.660 --> 00:14:25.430 align:middle line:84%
says God puts his
words upon our hearts.

00:14:25.430 --> 00:14:27.770 align:middle line:84%
And the rabbis ask a
question about that verse.

00:14:27.770 --> 00:14:29.330 align:middle line:90%
They say, why upon our hearts?

00:14:29.330 --> 00:14:30.818 align:middle line:90%
Why not in our hearts?

00:14:30.818 --> 00:14:33.360 align:middle line:84%
Certainly, if God has the power
to put words upon our hearts,

00:14:33.360 --> 00:14:35.390 align:middle line:84%
God has power to put
words within our hearts.

00:14:35.390 --> 00:14:38.870 align:middle line:84%
And the answer the sages
give is so powerful.

00:14:38.870 --> 00:14:42.230 align:middle line:84%
They say that God puts
God's words upon our hearts,

00:14:42.230 --> 00:14:45.380 align:middle line:84%
and it isn't until
our hearts are broken

00:14:45.380 --> 00:14:46.820 align:middle line:90%
that the words can enter.

00:14:46.820 --> 00:14:47.630 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Open.

00:14:47.630 --> 00:14:48.685 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: So beautiful.

00:14:48.685 --> 00:14:49.485 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes.

00:14:49.485 --> 00:14:50.210 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: Right?

00:14:50.210 --> 00:14:50.750 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: It's true.

00:14:50.750 --> 00:14:51.550 align:middle line:90%
It does take--

00:14:51.550 --> 00:14:54.920 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: So it's in the
breaking, ironically

00:14:54.920 --> 00:14:56.300 align:middle line:90%
and paradoxically.

00:14:56.300 --> 00:15:00.800 align:middle line:84%
It's in the break that we
become, in a way, more whole.

00:15:00.800 --> 00:15:02.960 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: The healing can begin.

00:15:02.960 --> 00:15:05.130 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: More whole than
prior to the brokenness.

00:15:05.130 --> 00:15:05.930 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes.

00:15:05.930 --> 00:15:10.430 align:middle line:84%
Well, I look at people who have
to willingly go through pain

00:15:10.430 --> 00:15:12.823 align:middle line:90%
in order to help humanity.

00:15:12.823 --> 00:15:14.240 align:middle line:84%
I mean, there's a
lot of women who

00:15:14.240 --> 00:15:17.900 align:middle line:84%
have been speaking out
about sexual abuse that

00:15:17.900 --> 00:15:19.890 align:middle line:90%
has been going on for decades.

00:15:19.890 --> 00:15:21.560 align:middle line:84%
And these women
knew what they were

00:15:21.560 --> 00:15:25.370 align:middle line:84%
headed into was
scrutiny and defamation

00:15:25.370 --> 00:15:28.112 align:middle line:84%
and getting ostracized
by their communities.

00:15:28.112 --> 00:15:29.570 align:middle line:84%
And they willingly
walking into it.

00:15:29.570 --> 00:15:32.300 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: And my guess
is-- now, I know people

00:15:32.300 --> 00:15:33.610 align:middle line:90%
on both sides of this.

00:15:33.610 --> 00:15:35.180 align:middle line:90%
I know some of the men.

00:15:35.180 --> 00:15:38.510 align:middle line:90%
I know some of the women.

00:15:38.510 --> 00:15:46.070 align:middle line:84%
I would guess that while
these individual women are,

00:15:46.070 --> 00:15:49.430 align:middle line:84%
of course, creating a
larger social change,

00:15:49.430 --> 00:15:55.190 align:middle line:84%
my hunch is that they're
speaking this truth more to be

00:15:55.190 --> 00:15:57.350 align:middle line:84%
worthy to their own
suffering and change

00:15:57.350 --> 00:15:58.940 align:middle line:90%
their own lives for the better.

00:15:58.940 --> 00:16:01.520 align:middle line:84%
Because they don't want to
live with this dark secret--

00:16:01.520 --> 00:16:02.690 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Anymore.

00:16:02.690 --> 00:16:05.030 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: --any longer,
because it's a prison.

00:16:05.030 --> 00:16:08.390 align:middle line:84%
And they don't want to be
in that prison of shame.

00:16:08.390 --> 00:16:13.490 align:middle line:84%
And it is that personal decision
to grow from the darkness

00:16:13.490 --> 00:16:16.070 align:middle line:84%
into the light that
also can lead, yes,

00:16:16.070 --> 00:16:18.410 align:middle line:84%
an entire country, nation,
or world into the light.

00:16:18.410 --> 00:16:21.320 align:middle line:84%
But it ultimately begins
first, if it's authentic,

00:16:21.320 --> 00:16:24.870 align:middle line:84%
it begins first right
here, not out there.

00:16:24.870 --> 00:16:26.990 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So there are
examples where pain happens

00:16:26.990 --> 00:16:28.650 align:middle line:90%
and suffering happens to you.

00:16:28.650 --> 00:16:30.440 align:middle line:84%
And it also can be
something you go

00:16:30.440 --> 00:16:33.230 align:middle line:84%
towards for a total
transformation.

00:16:33.230 --> 00:16:34.960 align:middle line:90%
There's so many different ways.

00:16:34.960 --> 00:16:36.710 align:middle line:84%
Let's take a look here
at this great video

00:16:36.710 --> 00:16:39.410 align:middle line:84%
that you did about the book
"More Beautiful Than Before."

00:16:39.410 --> 00:16:41.318 align:middle line:90%
Take a look.

00:16:41.318 --> 00:16:42.335 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:16:42.335 --> 00:16:44.750 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: You matter because
you were created in a way

00:16:44.750 --> 00:16:47.150 align:middle line:84%
unlike any other
person on Earth.

00:16:47.150 --> 00:16:48.320 align:middle line:90%
You are unique.

00:16:48.320 --> 00:16:50.060 align:middle line:90%
[ELECTRICITY CRACKLING]

00:16:50.060 --> 00:16:53.690 align:middle line:84%
Your pain, your wounds,
your scars and weakness

00:16:53.690 --> 00:16:58.790 align:middle line:84%
have made you kind, powerful,
gentle, and wise in new ways.

00:16:58.790 --> 00:17:03.120 align:middle line:84%
They have made you beautiful
in a way unlike anyone else.

00:17:03.120 --> 00:17:07.339 align:middle line:84%
The most advanced robot on Earth
cannot begin to approach who

00:17:07.339 --> 00:17:10.280 align:middle line:84%
you are and what you bring
to others because of what

00:17:10.280 --> 00:17:12.560 align:middle line:90%
your pain has taught you.

00:17:12.560 --> 00:17:15.349 align:middle line:84%
Do not come out of
hell empty-handed.

00:17:15.349 --> 00:17:18.410 align:middle line:84%
Do not let your
suffering be in vain.

00:17:18.410 --> 00:17:19.940 align:middle line:90%
You matter.

00:17:19.940 --> 00:17:20.740 align:middle line:90%
Live like in.

00:17:20.740 --> 00:17:24.099 align:middle line:90%


00:17:24.099 --> 00:17:26.050 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So you said in
there, don't come out

00:17:26.050 --> 00:17:27.460 align:middle line:90%
of hell empty-handed.

00:17:27.460 --> 00:17:28.940 align:middle line:90%
What do you mean by that?

00:17:28.940 --> 00:17:32.230 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: Well, what I mean is
that sooner or later, every one

00:17:32.230 --> 00:17:33.660 align:middle line:90%
of us walks through hell.

00:17:33.660 --> 00:17:35.810 align:middle line:84%
You know, there are
many forms of hell.

00:17:35.810 --> 00:17:39.340 align:middle line:90%
There's the hell of divorce.

00:17:39.340 --> 00:17:41.668 align:middle line:90%
There's the hell of cancer.

00:17:41.668 --> 00:17:43.210 align:middle line:84%
There's the hell of
a kid in trouble.

00:17:43.210 --> 00:17:46.000 align:middle line:84%
There's the hell of
Alzheimer's and dementia.

00:17:46.000 --> 00:17:48.500 align:middle line:84%
There's a hell of public
shame and embarrassment.

00:17:48.500 --> 00:17:50.167 align:middle line:90%
There's a hell of being hurt.

00:17:50.167 --> 00:17:52.000 align:middle line:84%
And by the way, the
hell of hurting another,

00:17:52.000 --> 00:17:54.680 align:middle line:90%
which is its own world of pain.

00:17:54.680 --> 00:17:56.200 align:middle line:90%
There's the hell of grief.

00:17:56.200 --> 00:18:00.250 align:middle line:84%
There are many, many forms
of help through which

00:18:00.250 --> 00:18:02.800 align:middle line:90%
every human being must walk.

00:18:02.800 --> 00:18:08.260 align:middle line:84%
And my hope is that no one
has to walk through hell

00:18:08.260 --> 00:18:10.090 align:middle line:90%
and come out empty-handed.

00:18:10.090 --> 00:18:12.820 align:middle line:84%
Don't come out of
hell empty-handed.

00:18:12.820 --> 00:18:15.370 align:middle line:84%
Make something of
your suffering.

00:18:15.370 --> 00:18:18.130 align:middle line:90%
Be worthy of your suffering.

00:18:18.130 --> 00:18:21.790 align:middle line:84%
Transform yourself, as a
result of that suffering,

00:18:21.790 --> 00:18:25.270 align:middle line:84%
into a more compassionate
and wise human being.

00:18:25.270 --> 00:18:26.560 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: It does so much.

00:18:26.560 --> 00:18:28.420 align:middle line:84%
It makes so much
sense, because it

00:18:28.420 --> 00:18:32.200 align:middle line:84%
makes sense of the
suffering, eventually,

00:18:32.200 --> 00:18:35.450 align:middle line:84%
after you've put yourself
back together and recovered,

00:18:35.450 --> 00:18:36.515 align:middle line:90%
which takes a while.

00:18:36.515 --> 00:18:37.390 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: Yes, it can.

00:18:37.390 --> 00:18:38.380 align:middle line:90%
It can take years.

00:18:38.380 --> 00:18:39.910 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Especially if
there's reason resentment.

00:18:39.910 --> 00:18:42.452 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: I wouldn't even say it
makes sense of the suffering,

00:18:42.452 --> 00:18:46.175 align:middle line:84%
because some forms of suffering
are beyond any human capacity--

00:18:46.175 --> 00:18:47.050 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: This is true.

00:18:47.050 --> 00:18:48.550 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: --to make sense of.

00:18:48.550 --> 00:18:51.850 align:middle line:84%
What it does is
it makes something

00:18:51.850 --> 00:18:55.420 align:middle line:84%
meaningful of the
suffering, right?

00:18:55.420 --> 00:19:00.100 align:middle line:84%
That you can take something
that lacks meaning and sense

00:19:00.100 --> 00:19:04.030 align:middle line:84%
entirely and use it to
create greater meaning

00:19:04.030 --> 00:19:05.420 align:middle line:90%
in your own life.

00:19:05.420 --> 00:19:07.060 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: I really
don't know how you can

00:19:07.060 --> 00:19:08.968 align:middle line:90%
do that when you lose a child.

00:19:08.968 --> 00:19:10.510 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: Well, let's
talk about that.

00:19:10.510 --> 00:19:12.870 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Yeah, the babies
and the little ones.

00:19:12.870 --> 00:19:13.670 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:19:13.670 --> 00:19:16.450 align:middle line:90%


00:19:16.450 --> 00:19:20.920 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: I never try to make
sense of the death of a child.

00:19:20.920 --> 00:19:23.800 align:middle line:84%
Very often, what I
don't say to someone

00:19:23.800 --> 00:19:26.170 align:middle line:84%
is far more important
than what I do say.

00:19:26.170 --> 00:19:30.670 align:middle line:84%
I never say, at least
she's in a better place.

00:19:30.670 --> 00:19:35.312 align:middle line:84%
I never say, you know, at least
she's no longer suffering.

00:19:35.312 --> 00:19:37.270 align:middle line:84%
Why does she have to
suffer in the first place?

00:19:37.270 --> 00:19:38.070 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right.

00:19:38.070 --> 00:19:41.320 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: I never say,
God doesn't give you

00:19:41.320 --> 00:19:42.580 align:middle line:90%
more than you can bear.

00:19:42.580 --> 00:19:46.360 align:middle line:84%
Who is God to decide what
one human being can bear?

00:19:46.360 --> 00:19:50.260 align:middle line:84%
I never try to make
sense of the madness.

00:19:50.260 --> 00:19:56.530 align:middle line:84%
What I do say to people who
suffer the death of a child--

00:19:56.530 --> 00:20:00.040 align:middle line:84%
the only helpful and
honest thing I can say--

00:20:00.040 --> 00:20:07.090 align:middle line:84%
is, it won't always
hurt this much.

00:20:07.090 --> 00:20:07.980 align:middle line:90%
It gets better.

00:20:07.980 --> 00:20:09.730 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: That's a really
nice thing to say.

00:20:09.730 --> 00:20:11.700 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: And it's the truth.

00:20:11.700 --> 00:20:14.260 align:middle line:84%
And I will tell you, as
a guy who, unfortunately,

00:20:14.260 --> 00:20:17.800 align:middle line:84%
has had to see many people
through the death of children--

00:20:17.800 --> 00:20:20.920 align:middle line:84%
sometimes from cancer, sometimes
from suicide, sometimes

00:20:20.920 --> 00:20:23.680 align:middle line:84%
from a car accident,
sometimes from an incredibly

00:20:23.680 --> 00:20:25.550 align:middle line:90%
rare disease.

00:20:25.550 --> 00:20:30.820 align:middle line:84%
I will tell you that, years
later, I see these parents,

00:20:30.820 --> 00:20:34.000 align:middle line:84%
and they're enjoying that
piece of chocolate cake.

00:20:34.000 --> 00:20:37.180 align:middle line:84%
And they're laughing
at the movies.

00:20:37.180 --> 00:20:40.750 align:middle line:84%
And they're enjoying their
children and their family.

00:20:40.750 --> 00:20:42.610 align:middle line:90%
You know, it's an amputation.

00:20:42.610 --> 00:20:44.800 align:middle line:90%
It's always missing.

00:20:44.800 --> 00:20:46.750 align:middle line:84%
They poet said,
"Death is the absence

00:20:46.750 --> 00:20:48.310 align:middle line:90%
that is forever present."

00:20:48.310 --> 00:20:51.040 align:middle line:84%
It's an absence that
is forever present,

00:20:51.040 --> 00:20:56.350 align:middle line:84%
but it does not mean
the end of life and joy.

00:20:56.350 --> 00:21:00.190 align:middle line:84%
And by the way, I think the
important point, as well,

00:21:00.190 --> 00:21:03.790 align:middle line:84%
is that these parents survive
the death of their children,

00:21:03.790 --> 00:21:07.660 align:middle line:84%
not because they are
extraordinary human beings.

00:21:07.660 --> 00:21:10.660 align:middle line:84%
They survive because they
are ordinary human beings,

00:21:10.660 --> 00:21:12.520 align:middle line:90%
like you and like me.

00:21:12.520 --> 00:21:15.950 align:middle line:90%
It is built into us to somehow--

00:21:15.950 --> 00:21:16.750 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Cope.

00:21:16.750 --> 00:21:18.100 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: --go on.

00:21:18.100 --> 00:21:19.520 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: To cope.

00:21:19.520 --> 00:21:21.490 align:middle line:84%
But you can't find
meaning in it.

00:21:21.490 --> 00:21:24.010 align:middle line:84%
So you can't find meaning in
every bit of suffering, right?

00:21:24.010 --> 00:21:26.350 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: I wouldn't say that
there's no meaning in it.

00:21:26.350 --> 00:21:29.200 align:middle line:84%
I would say there's
no reason for it,

00:21:29.200 --> 00:21:31.630 align:middle line:84%
but that doesn't mean
it's devoid of meaning.

00:21:31.630 --> 00:21:38.420 align:middle line:84%
For example, it changes
the way you approach

00:21:38.420 --> 00:21:40.700 align:middle line:90%
others who are suffering.

00:21:40.700 --> 00:21:42.477 align:middle line:84%
It makes you a different
kind of friend--

00:21:42.477 --> 00:21:43.310 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: That's true.

00:21:43.310 --> 00:21:45.320 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: --a different
kind of parent,

00:21:45.320 --> 00:21:49.290 align:middle line:84%
a different kind of spouse,
a different kind of teacher,

00:21:49.290 --> 00:21:51.980 align:middle line:84%
a different kind of physician,
a different kind of accountant.

00:21:51.980 --> 00:21:57.710 align:middle line:84%
It changes you in ways that
are not entirely negative, many

00:21:57.710 --> 00:21:59.090 align:middle line:90%
of them quite positive.

00:21:59.090 --> 00:22:01.440 align:middle line:84%
But it's not worth
it, let's be honest.

00:22:01.440 --> 00:22:02.240 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: No.

00:22:02.240 --> 00:22:03.040 align:middle line:90%
No.

00:22:03.040 --> 00:22:06.770 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: But it's not entirely
without worth and value.

00:22:06.770 --> 00:22:09.380 align:middle line:84%
I wouldn't wish it
on my worst enemy.

00:22:09.380 --> 00:22:10.970 align:middle line:90%
That's not my point.

00:22:10.970 --> 00:22:13.560 align:middle line:90%


00:22:13.560 --> 00:22:15.850 align:middle line:84%
I think that you're
correct in this sense--

00:22:15.850 --> 00:22:17.450 align:middle line:90%
there's no why.

00:22:17.450 --> 00:22:18.320 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right.

00:22:18.320 --> 00:22:20.403 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: Part of what I
do when people are sitting

00:22:20.403 --> 00:22:24.410 align:middle line:84%
on in my office on what
I call my couch of tears

00:22:24.410 --> 00:22:26.660 align:middle line:84%
is I try to move them
as quickly as possible

00:22:26.660 --> 00:22:29.240 align:middle line:90%
from the why to what.

00:22:29.240 --> 00:22:32.390 align:middle line:84%
Because why is a cul-de-sac, and
you just go around and around

00:22:32.390 --> 00:22:33.420 align:middle line:90%
and around and around.

00:22:33.420 --> 00:22:36.530 align:middle line:84%
There is no why to the
innocent suffering.

00:22:36.530 --> 00:22:38.870 align:middle line:84%
There is no why to
the death of a child.

00:22:38.870 --> 00:22:42.410 align:middle line:84%
There is no why to cancer cells
gone mad and metastasizing

00:22:42.410 --> 00:22:43.220 align:middle line:90%
in your body.

00:22:43.220 --> 00:22:45.860 align:middle line:90%
There is no why, you know?

00:22:45.860 --> 00:22:49.027 align:middle line:84%
People always say to me, you
know, your book is so good.

00:22:49.027 --> 00:22:51.110 align:middle line:84%
It reminds me of that book
"When Bad Things Happen

00:22:51.110 --> 00:22:53.270 align:middle line:84%
to Good People,"
Harold Kushner's book.

00:22:53.270 --> 00:22:56.600 align:middle line:84%
And I tell people, that's
not what the book was called.

00:22:56.600 --> 00:22:59.480 align:middle line:84%
The title of that famous book
is "When Bad Things Happen

00:22:59.480 --> 00:23:01.220 align:middle line:90%
to Good People," not why.

00:23:01.220 --> 00:23:02.870 align:middle line:84%
Everyone wishes
someone could write

00:23:02.870 --> 00:23:05.930 align:middle line:84%
a book called "Why Bad Things--"
but you can't write that book.

00:23:05.930 --> 00:23:07.790 align:middle line:90%
The book was called when.

00:23:07.790 --> 00:23:11.090 align:middle line:84%
So I try to move people
off of why to what.

00:23:11.090 --> 00:23:13.100 align:middle line:84%
OK, what, given that
this has happened,

00:23:13.100 --> 00:23:15.090 align:middle line:84%
are you going to
do with your life?

00:23:15.090 --> 00:23:18.330 align:middle line:84%
How are you going to
live going forward?

00:23:18.330 --> 00:23:21.433 align:middle line:84%
That's the only productive
thing we can do.

00:23:21.433 --> 00:23:22.850 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: That's the
only thing that

00:23:22.850 --> 00:23:24.650 align:middle line:90%
can really truly transform you.

00:23:24.650 --> 00:23:27.030 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: And why is a dead end.

00:23:27.030 --> 00:23:29.063 align:middle line:84%
And being good doesn't
protect you from evil.

00:23:29.063 --> 00:23:30.980 align:middle line:84%
It's like expecting the
bull not to charge you

00:23:30.980 --> 00:23:32.270 align:middle line:90%
because you're a vegetarian.

00:23:32.270 --> 00:23:34.090 align:middle line:90%
It's not how it works.

00:23:34.090 --> 00:23:34.890 align:middle line:90%
Right?

00:23:34.890 --> 00:23:36.320 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: I know, unfortunately.

00:23:36.320 --> 00:23:39.170 align:middle line:84%
Is there a difference between
the suffering of someone

00:23:39.170 --> 00:23:42.755 align:middle line:84%
who is in physical pain versus
someone who has had loss

00:23:42.755 --> 00:23:43.880 align:middle line:90%
and is going through grief?

00:23:43.880 --> 00:23:44.390 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: Emotional pain.

00:23:44.390 --> 00:23:45.200 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yeah, emotional pain.

00:23:45.200 --> 00:23:46.100 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: Well,
interestingly enough,

00:23:46.100 --> 00:23:48.350 align:middle line:84%
they both affect the
same region of the brain.

00:23:48.350 --> 00:23:51.110 align:middle line:84%
Physical and emotional
pain affect the same region

00:23:51.110 --> 00:23:52.130 align:middle line:90%
of the brain.

00:23:52.130 --> 00:23:55.490 align:middle line:84%
The one difference is-- and
this is why, on some level,

00:23:55.490 --> 00:23:59.630 align:middle line:84%
physical pain can be
easier in the long run--

00:23:59.630 --> 00:24:03.890 align:middle line:84%
is that you can't re-summon
the pain of physical pain.

00:24:03.890 --> 00:24:06.622 align:middle line:84%
You can't re-feel it,
literally re-feel it.

00:24:06.622 --> 00:24:07.580 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Once it's gone.

00:24:07.580 --> 00:24:09.330 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: Once it's
gone, correct.

00:24:09.330 --> 00:24:12.470 align:middle line:84%
However, the pain of loss,
the pain of a divorce,

00:24:12.470 --> 00:24:15.260 align:middle line:84%
the pain of public shame,
whatever it is, you

00:24:15.260 --> 00:24:18.650 align:middle line:84%
can revisit over and
over and over and over

00:24:18.650 --> 00:24:19.550 align:middle line:90%
again in your mind.

00:24:19.550 --> 00:24:21.560 align:middle line:84%
Who doesn't remember
their first broken heart?

00:24:21.560 --> 00:24:22.727 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: In your mind, yes.

00:24:22.727 --> 00:24:24.560 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: And so there
is a subtle difference

00:24:24.560 --> 00:24:25.360 align:middle line:90%
between the two.

00:24:25.360 --> 00:24:27.920 align:middle line:84%
But I think they both
present the same challenges

00:24:27.920 --> 00:24:30.120 align:middle line:90%
and the same opportunity.

00:24:30.120 --> 00:24:30.920 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes.

00:24:30.920 --> 00:24:36.560 align:middle line:84%
Now, did you grow up in an area
where you wanted to be a rabbi?

00:24:36.560 --> 00:24:39.180 align:middle line:84%
Or you ever had an idea
of wanting to write

00:24:39.180 --> 00:24:41.150 align:middle line:90%
about things like suffering?

00:24:41.150 --> 00:24:42.230 align:middle line:90%
Where did you start?

00:24:42.230 --> 00:24:44.880 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: The odds of me ending
up where I am were very slim.

00:24:44.880 --> 00:24:45.680 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Really?

00:24:45.680 --> 00:24:47.960 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: First of all, I
grew up in a working class,

00:24:47.960 --> 00:24:49.020 align:middle line:90%
blue-collar family.

00:24:49.020 --> 00:24:51.350 align:middle line:90%
My dad owned a junkyard.

00:24:51.350 --> 00:24:54.922 align:middle line:84%
Not a metal recycling
plant, a junkyard.

00:24:54.922 --> 00:24:55.880 align:middle line:90%
I was one of five kids.

00:24:55.880 --> 00:24:58.010 align:middle line:84%
There were seven of us in a
three bedroom, one bathroom

00:24:58.010 --> 00:24:58.820 align:middle line:90%
house.

00:24:58.820 --> 00:25:02.100 align:middle line:84%
You know, I grew up
in a very modest way.

00:25:02.100 --> 00:25:03.650 align:middle line:84%
I grew up in a
family that was not

00:25:03.650 --> 00:25:07.160 align:middle line:84%
particularly religious,
although culturally very Jewish.

00:25:07.160 --> 00:25:11.090 align:middle line:84%
I knew almost as much Yiddish in
kindergarten as I did English.

00:25:11.090 --> 00:25:13.560 align:middle line:84%
But we weren't a particularly
religious family.

00:25:13.560 --> 00:25:17.780 align:middle line:84%
And because of this
kind of very demanding,

00:25:17.780 --> 00:25:22.190 align:middle line:90%
hard-driving father that I had--

00:25:22.190 --> 00:25:24.140 align:middle line:84%
and because of his
background, having grown up

00:25:24.140 --> 00:25:27.380 align:middle line:84%
on public assistance as a
child through the Depression--

00:25:27.380 --> 00:25:30.980 align:middle line:84%
almost any creative pursuit was
dismissed as a waste of time

00:25:30.980 --> 00:25:31.877 align:middle line:90%
when I was a child.

00:25:31.877 --> 00:25:32.960 align:middle line:90%
You want to be a musician?

00:25:32.960 --> 00:25:33.460 align:middle line:90%
Forget it.

00:25:33.460 --> 00:25:34.140 align:middle line:90%
You want to be an actor?

00:25:34.140 --> 00:25:34.640 align:middle line:90%
Forget it.

00:25:34.640 --> 00:25:35.300 align:middle line:90%
You want to be a writer?

00:25:35.300 --> 00:25:35.810 align:middle line:90%
Forget it.

00:25:35.810 --> 00:25:37.185 align:middle line:84%
You're going to
go to law school,

00:25:37.185 --> 00:25:39.530 align:middle line:84%
and then you're going to
take over the junkyard.

00:25:39.530 --> 00:25:46.400 align:middle line:84%
The one creative pursuit,
the one creative endeavor

00:25:46.400 --> 00:25:50.020 align:middle line:84%
that was permissible in my home
as a kid was the synagogue.

00:25:50.020 --> 00:25:52.897 align:middle line:84%
It was the only place they
would drive the kids to.

00:25:52.897 --> 00:25:54.230 align:middle line:90%
Otherwise, you were on your own.

00:25:54.230 --> 00:25:55.647 align:middle line:84%
You want to go to
hockey practice?

00:25:55.647 --> 00:25:57.770 align:middle line:90%
Good luck to you.

00:25:57.770 --> 00:26:01.010 align:middle line:84%
So you know, you don't
have to be Sigmund Freud

00:26:01.010 --> 00:26:02.630 align:middle line:84%
to connect these
dots as to why I

00:26:02.630 --> 00:26:06.657 align:middle line:84%
gravitated toward that one
place that was about the spirit.

00:26:06.657 --> 00:26:07.490 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: And freedom.

00:26:07.490 --> 00:26:08.360 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: It was freedom.

00:26:08.360 --> 00:26:09.200 align:middle line:90%
It was spirit.

00:26:09.200 --> 00:26:10.040 align:middle line:90%
It was music.

00:26:10.040 --> 00:26:11.090 align:middle line:90%
It was art.

00:26:11.090 --> 00:26:14.075 align:middle line:90%
It was stories, so many stories.

00:26:14.075 --> 00:26:15.950 align:middle line:84%
I mean, what is the
Bible if not a collection

00:26:15.950 --> 00:26:18.050 align:middle line:84%
of stories about
the human condition?

00:26:18.050 --> 00:26:21.440 align:middle line:84%
So for me, the
synagogue was an oasis

00:26:21.440 --> 00:26:25.850 align:middle line:84%
in this blue-collared desert of
dirt and grease and hard work.

00:26:25.850 --> 00:26:28.380 align:middle line:84%
And so that that's
a big part of it.

00:26:28.380 --> 00:26:30.680 align:middle line:84%
And the other thing is
I thought very serious

00:26:30.680 --> 00:26:33.005 align:middle line:90%
about going into politics.

00:26:33.005 --> 00:26:34.655 align:middle line:84%
I was an undergraduate
at Northwestern.

00:26:34.655 --> 00:26:36.530 align:middle line:84%
I was in the writing
program at Northwestern.

00:26:36.530 --> 00:26:40.390 align:middle line:84%
But I took a summer
and part of a semester

00:26:40.390 --> 00:26:42.520 align:middle line:84%
off and volunteered on
a congressional campaign

00:26:42.520 --> 00:26:44.423 align:middle line:90%
in Southern Illinois in 1980.

00:26:44.423 --> 00:26:46.840 align:middle line:84%
And I worked with a bunch of
the guys who ended up running

00:26:46.840 --> 00:26:48.490 align:middle line:90%
the Clinton White House.

00:26:48.490 --> 00:26:51.460 align:middle line:84%
And that was the other
thing I was interested in,

00:26:51.460 --> 00:26:54.130 align:middle line:84%
is I think I want to be a
senator and change the world.

00:26:54.130 --> 00:26:55.990 align:middle line:84%
When I got on the
inside of politics

00:26:55.990 --> 00:26:59.490 align:middle line:84%
and saw what it was really about
and who it was really about,

00:26:59.490 --> 00:27:01.360 align:middle line:90%
I wanted nothing to do with it.

00:27:01.360 --> 00:27:03.670 align:middle line:84%
It was a very negative
experience for me,

00:27:03.670 --> 00:27:07.030 align:middle line:84%
because it was just about
money and being predatory.

00:27:07.030 --> 00:27:08.620 align:middle line:90%
And I had no interest in that.

00:27:08.620 --> 00:27:11.980 align:middle line:84%
So that that campaign
really did me a favor

00:27:11.980 --> 00:27:14.260 align:middle line:84%
and just reaffirmed
my commitment

00:27:14.260 --> 00:27:17.222 align:middle line:90%
to pursue a life of the spirit.

00:27:17.222 --> 00:27:18.430 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Well, that, you have.

00:27:18.430 --> 00:27:22.610 align:middle line:84%
And the Wilshire Boulevard
Temple is a huge congregation.

00:27:22.610 --> 00:27:23.410 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: It is.

00:27:23.410 --> 00:27:26.250 align:middle line:84%
If Jews had a megachurch,
we think we would be it.

00:27:26.250 --> 00:27:29.540 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, we have three
campuses, 2,500 families.

00:27:29.540 --> 00:27:31.270 align:middle line:90%
And we have a school system.

00:27:31.270 --> 00:27:33.170 align:middle line:84%
We have two early
childhood centers,

00:27:33.170 --> 00:27:36.970 align:middle line:84%
two elementary schools, two
sleepaway camps in Malibu.

00:27:36.970 --> 00:27:39.790 align:middle line:84%
It's an amazing collection
of people and places,

00:27:39.790 --> 00:27:42.290 align:middle line:84%
and I'm incredibly,
incredibly proud of.

00:27:42.290 --> 00:27:44.590 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: It's also very
contemporary at the same time

00:27:44.590 --> 00:27:46.540 align:middle line:84%
it's holding on
to the tradition,

00:27:46.540 --> 00:27:48.373 align:middle line:84%
which there's something
to be said for that.

00:27:48.373 --> 00:27:49.957 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: Well, I
think it's essential.

00:27:49.957 --> 00:27:51.680 align:middle line:84%
I think we have to be
rooted in the past,

00:27:51.680 --> 00:27:53.930 align:middle line:84%
but we also have to be leaning
forward into the future

00:27:53.930 --> 00:27:56.390 align:middle line:84%
or we'll lose the
next generation.

00:27:56.390 --> 00:27:58.240 align:middle line:90%
And I wouldn't blame them a bit.

00:27:58.240 --> 00:28:02.410 align:middle line:84%
So I try very hard to be
both timely and timeless

00:28:02.410 --> 00:28:04.840 align:middle line:90%
in my messages.

00:28:04.840 --> 00:28:07.660 align:middle line:84%
Also, I work hard at hiring
a lot of young people, which

00:28:07.660 --> 00:28:09.230 align:middle line:90%
I think is very important well.

00:28:09.230 --> 00:28:11.680 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: But how do you
keep to that tradition

00:28:11.680 --> 00:28:16.120 align:middle line:84%
and honor the suffering of the
Jewish people at the same time

00:28:16.120 --> 00:28:19.660 align:middle line:84%
as be contemporary and move
the conversation forward?

00:28:19.660 --> 00:28:21.310 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: Well, you
know, Jewish history

00:28:21.310 --> 00:28:22.490 align:middle line:90%
is not only about suffering.

00:28:22.490 --> 00:28:23.290 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right.

00:28:23.290 --> 00:28:27.820 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: It's also about
poetry and music and stories

00:28:27.820 --> 00:28:30.520 align:middle line:90%
of deep faith and transcendence.

00:28:30.520 --> 00:28:33.540 align:middle line:84%
So it's not only about
suffering, you know.

00:28:33.540 --> 00:28:35.560 align:middle line:84%
And a lot of people
do allow that kind

00:28:35.560 --> 00:28:37.823 align:middle line:84%
of suffering to eclipse
the joy of Judaism,

00:28:37.823 --> 00:28:39.240 align:middle line:84%
and I think that's
a huge mistake.

00:28:39.240 --> 00:28:39.910 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right.

00:28:39.910 --> 00:28:41.980 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: You know, I gave
a sermon many years ago

00:28:41.980 --> 00:28:43.240 align:middle line:90%
that was pretty controversial.

00:28:43.240 --> 00:28:46.750 align:middle line:84%
And in it, I talked not about
forgetting the Holocaust,

00:28:46.750 --> 00:28:49.810 align:middle line:84%
but about transcending
the Holocaust.

00:28:49.810 --> 00:28:52.510 align:middle line:84%
That the last thing those
victims would have wanted

00:28:52.510 --> 00:28:57.020 align:middle line:84%
was for us to perpetuate or
embrace a joyless Judaism.

00:28:57.020 --> 00:28:57.820 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right.

00:28:57.820 --> 00:28:58.620 align:middle line:90%
Right.

00:28:58.620 --> 00:29:02.230 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: And so this is about
transcending oppression,

00:29:02.230 --> 00:29:03.310 align:middle line:90%
not forgetting it.

00:29:03.310 --> 00:29:06.850 align:middle line:84%
But also not being
identified by it.

00:29:06.850 --> 00:29:09.100 align:middle line:84%
Because darkness really
doesn't hold people.

00:29:09.100 --> 00:29:12.610 align:middle line:84%
You know, it's true that
those who forget history

00:29:12.610 --> 00:29:13.970 align:middle line:90%
are doomed to repeat it.

00:29:13.970 --> 00:29:18.520 align:middle line:84%
But it is also true that those
who only remember history

00:29:18.520 --> 00:29:19.790 align:middle line:90%
are also doomed to repeat it.

00:29:19.790 --> 00:29:20.590 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes.

00:29:20.590 --> 00:29:21.060 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: Right?

00:29:21.060 --> 00:29:21.860 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes.

00:29:21.860 --> 00:29:24.010 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: And so it is,
as you articulated,

00:29:24.010 --> 00:29:27.880 align:middle line:84%
this dichotomous tension between
past, present, and future,

00:29:27.880 --> 00:29:30.300 align:middle line:90%
and they're all important.

00:29:30.300 --> 00:29:33.790 align:middle line:84%
And I think we, at least, have
struck a pretty decent balance,

00:29:33.790 --> 00:29:35.482 align:middle line:90%
and it seems to be working.

00:29:35.482 --> 00:29:36.440 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: That's amazing.

00:29:36.440 --> 00:29:38.350 align:middle line:84%
I mean, the controversy
that you received

00:29:38.350 --> 00:29:39.960 align:middle line:90%
was the remembrance and the--

00:29:39.960 --> 00:29:42.760 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: How dare you forget.

00:29:42.760 --> 00:29:44.440 align:middle line:84%
And I didn't talk
about forgetting,

00:29:44.440 --> 00:29:46.130 align:middle line:84%
but I talked about
transcending it.

00:29:46.130 --> 00:29:48.580 align:middle line:84%
Because the truth is
for this generation

00:29:48.580 --> 00:29:52.640 align:middle line:84%
of American kids in general,
darkness doesn't hold them.

00:29:52.640 --> 00:29:53.440 align:middle line:90%
They want light.

00:29:53.440 --> 00:29:53.980 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: They do.

00:29:53.980 --> 00:29:54.938 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: They want joy.

00:29:54.938 --> 00:29:56.690 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: They do.

00:29:56.690 --> 00:29:57.490 align:middle line:90%
We all do.

00:29:57.490 --> 00:30:00.730 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: We all do, and to
define oneself by the darkness

00:30:00.730 --> 00:30:01.665 align:middle line:90%
is a mistake.

00:30:01.665 --> 00:30:02.540 align:middle line:90%
You have to honor it.

00:30:02.540 --> 00:30:04.082 align:middle line:84%
And this gets back
to this whole idea

00:30:04.082 --> 00:30:09.490 align:middle line:84%
of honoring your pain
without being defined by it.

00:30:09.490 --> 00:30:11.470 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: I am so glad
that you said that.

00:30:11.470 --> 00:30:13.900 align:middle line:84%
That is the basis
of what I believe

00:30:13.900 --> 00:30:16.250 align:middle line:84%
and what I have created
this show based on.

00:30:16.250 --> 00:30:17.250 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: Well, I'm glad.

00:30:17.250 --> 00:30:17.650 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yeah.

00:30:17.650 --> 00:30:18.240 align:middle line:90%
Thank you.

00:30:18.240 --> 00:30:19.370 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: We're kindred spirits.

00:30:19.370 --> 00:30:19.900 align:middle line:90%
We are.

00:30:19.900 --> 00:30:20.530 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: We are.

00:30:20.530 --> 00:30:21.500 align:middle line:90%
Take a look at this.

00:30:21.500 --> 00:30:22.600 align:middle line:84%
I want you to see
your rabbi leader

00:30:22.600 --> 00:30:23.860 align:middle line:90%
in action giving a sermon.

00:30:23.860 --> 00:30:25.090 align:middle line:90%
It's beautiful.

00:30:25.090 --> 00:30:30.160 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: So what have I
learned from 30 years of death

00:30:30.160 --> 00:30:32.680 align:middle line:84%
that I can share with
you on this evening, when

00:30:32.680 --> 00:30:36.970 align:middle line:84%
we are commanded to consider
our own deaths in order that we

00:30:36.970 --> 00:30:38.020 align:middle line:90%
might change our lives?

00:30:38.020 --> 00:30:41.930 align:middle line:90%


00:30:41.930 --> 00:30:43.720 align:middle line:84%
The first thing I have
learned about death

00:30:43.720 --> 00:30:49.210 align:middle line:84%
might surprise you,
which is there are

00:30:49.210 --> 00:30:54.460 align:middle line:90%
many things worse than dying.

00:30:54.460 --> 00:30:59.700 align:middle line:84%
I've held the hands of
hundreds of dying people.

00:30:59.700 --> 00:31:05.610 align:middle line:84%
It might amaze you to know
that not once, not one time,

00:31:05.610 --> 00:31:07.515 align:middle line:90%
has any of them been afraid.

00:31:07.515 --> 00:31:10.030 align:middle line:90%


00:31:10.030 --> 00:31:13.210 align:middle line:84%
There are rare exceptions,
but most people

00:31:13.210 --> 00:31:17.380 align:middle line:84%
die at the end of a very
long life or, if young,

00:31:17.380 --> 00:31:20.860 align:middle line:84%
after a long,
debilitating illness.

00:31:20.860 --> 00:31:24.640 align:middle line:84%
Age and disease have their
own rhythm and power.

00:31:24.640 --> 00:31:25.720 align:middle line:90%
They teach us.

00:31:25.720 --> 00:31:29.560 align:middle line:84%
They carry us along,
preparing us and the people

00:31:29.560 --> 00:31:32.870 align:middle line:90%
we love for death.

00:31:32.870 --> 00:31:38.465 align:middle line:84%
For most, death comes as
a sort of peaceful friend.

00:31:38.465 --> 00:31:41.040 align:middle line:90%


00:31:41.040 --> 00:31:44.160 align:middle line:84%
Most people are ready
to die the way we're all

00:31:44.160 --> 00:31:49.410 align:middle line:84%
ready to sleep after a very long
and terribly exhausting day.

00:31:49.410 --> 00:31:52.440 align:middle line:84%
We just want to pull
the covers up around us

00:31:52.440 --> 00:31:57.000 align:middle line:84%
and settle in for
the peace of it all.

00:31:57.000 --> 00:32:00.180 align:middle line:84%
We are not anxious
about sleeping.

00:32:00.180 --> 00:32:01.650 align:middle line:90%
We are not depressed.

00:32:01.650 --> 00:32:04.860 align:middle line:90%
We are not afraid.

00:32:04.860 --> 00:32:08.740 align:middle line:84%
The rabbis called death
[SPEAKING HEBREW]----

00:32:08.740 --> 00:32:10.925 align:middle line:90%
perfect sleep.

00:32:10.925 --> 00:32:13.470 align:middle line:90%


00:32:13.470 --> 00:32:19.320 align:middle line:84%
Disease and age and life
itself prepare us for death,

00:32:19.320 --> 00:32:24.330 align:middle line:84%
and when it is really
our time, death

00:32:24.330 --> 00:32:26.590 align:middle line:90%
is as natural a thing as life.

00:32:26.590 --> 00:32:29.810 align:middle line:90%


00:32:29.810 --> 00:32:32.240 align:middle line:90%
Here's some good news--

00:32:32.240 --> 00:32:38.120 align:middle line:84%
this means that if you
are afraid of dying,

00:32:38.120 --> 00:32:40.460 align:middle line:90%
it's not your day.

00:32:40.460 --> 00:32:43.960 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Was this sermon
on Rosh Hashanah?

00:32:43.960 --> 00:32:46.060 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: That
sermon was actually

00:32:46.060 --> 00:32:49.990 align:middle line:84%
given on the eve of
Yom Kippur, called

00:32:49.990 --> 00:32:53.050 align:middle line:84%
Kol Nidre, the holiest
night of the year for Jews.

00:32:53.050 --> 00:32:56.120 align:middle line:84%
And it's an evening
that really does--

00:32:56.120 --> 00:32:57.700 align:middle line:84%
if you see the
whole sermon, it's

00:32:57.700 --> 00:33:02.350 align:middle line:84%
an evening that's meant to force
us to contemplate our deaths so

00:33:02.350 --> 00:33:04.310 align:middle line:84%
that we might take our
lives more seriously.

00:33:04.310 --> 00:33:05.110 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Wow.

00:33:05.110 --> 00:33:05.410 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: Yeah.

00:33:05.410 --> 00:33:07.000 align:middle line:10%
There's a lot of
imagery and metaphors

00:33:07.000 --> 00:33:09.580 align:middle line:10%
in the liturgy and
the choreography

00:33:09.580 --> 00:33:13.720 align:middle line:10%
of the service that force us
to think about our own deaths.

00:33:13.720 --> 00:33:15.890 align:middle line:10%
We fast because
the dead don't eat.

00:33:15.890 --> 00:33:17.020 align:middle line:90%
We don't drink.

00:33:17.020 --> 00:33:19.330 align:middle line:84%
We wear white because the
traditional Jew is buried

00:33:19.330 --> 00:33:21.100 align:middle line:90%
in a white burial shroud.

00:33:21.100 --> 00:33:24.850 align:middle line:84%
We begin with an empty what we
call arc on the pulpit, which

00:33:24.850 --> 00:33:25.930 align:middle line:90%
holds the Torahs.

00:33:25.930 --> 00:33:29.200 align:middle line:84%
And the Hebrew word for arc
and the Hebrew word for coffin

00:33:29.200 --> 00:33:30.590 align:middle line:90%
are the same word.

00:33:30.590 --> 00:33:35.020 align:middle line:84%
So we begin the evening
staring into an empty coffin.

00:33:35.020 --> 00:33:38.410 align:middle line:84%
And so there are all these
ways in which that evening

00:33:38.410 --> 00:33:41.290 align:middle line:84%
is structured to force
us to contemplate

00:33:41.290 --> 00:33:46.660 align:middle line:84%
our deaths, simply and
purely, so that we might

00:33:46.660 --> 00:33:49.160 align:middle line:90%
think about changing our lives.

00:33:49.160 --> 00:33:50.410 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: And that's Yom Kippur.

00:33:50.410 --> 00:33:52.162 align:middle line:84%
And then after that
is Rosh Hashanah?

00:33:52.162 --> 00:33:53.620 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: Rosh
Hashanah precedes it.

00:33:53.620 --> 00:33:54.060 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Precedes?

00:33:54.060 --> 00:33:54.820 align:middle line:90%
It can you explain--

00:33:54.820 --> 00:33:56.530 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: Which I'll tell you
something also very interesting

00:33:56.530 --> 00:33:58.238 align:middle line:84%
based on what we were
just talking about,

00:33:58.238 --> 00:34:00.730 align:middle line:84%
about privilege and
light over darkness.

00:34:00.730 --> 00:34:04.630 align:middle line:84%
So Rosh Hashanah is the holiday
that affirms the new year,

00:34:04.630 --> 00:34:07.780 align:middle line:84%
celebrates the new year,
embraces the new year.

00:34:07.780 --> 00:34:11.080 align:middle line:84%
And Yom Kippur is the
holiday on our festival

00:34:11.080 --> 00:34:14.590 align:middle line:84%
on which we atone for our
sins and regrets and mistakes

00:34:14.590 --> 00:34:15.469 align:middle line:90%
from the past year.

00:34:15.469 --> 00:34:18.250 align:middle line:84%
Now, it's structured
counterintuitively, right?

00:34:18.250 --> 00:34:20.020 align:middle line:84%
You would think,
first, you would

00:34:20.020 --> 00:34:22.810 align:middle line:84%
think about the sins of
the past, clean the slate,

00:34:22.810 --> 00:34:24.880 align:middle line:84%
and then go forward to
embrace the new year.

00:34:24.880 --> 00:34:28.030 align:middle line:84%
But the rabbis constructed
it in just the opposite way.

00:34:28.030 --> 00:34:29.800 align:middle line:90%
Why?

00:34:29.800 --> 00:34:34.570 align:middle line:84%
It is a demonstration of
our faith in our own ability

00:34:34.570 --> 00:34:37.030 align:middle line:84%
to move forward
past our mistakes

00:34:37.030 --> 00:34:40.570 align:middle line:84%
and our faith in God
and goodness and light.

00:34:40.570 --> 00:34:42.740 align:middle line:90%
First we celebrate, then--

00:34:42.740 --> 00:34:43.540 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Life.

00:34:43.540 --> 00:34:45.300 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: --we atone.

00:34:45.300 --> 00:34:47.650 align:middle line:84%
It's a very
beautiful thing, when

00:34:47.650 --> 00:34:51.250 align:middle line:84%
you think about it, that we
privilege light over darkness.

00:34:51.250 --> 00:34:54.670 align:middle line:84%
We don't deny the darkness,
but light comes first.

00:34:54.670 --> 00:34:56.659 align:middle line:84%
And this is built into
Judaism in many ways.

00:34:56.659 --> 00:35:00.430 align:middle line:84%
For example, the Talmud says a
wedding processional interrupts

00:35:00.430 --> 00:35:02.300 align:middle line:90%
a funeral procession.

00:35:02.300 --> 00:35:03.100 align:middle line:90%
Right?

00:35:03.100 --> 00:35:03.520 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Does it?

00:35:03.520 --> 00:35:04.320 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:35:04.320 --> 00:35:05.500 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: It does.

00:35:05.500 --> 00:35:08.590 align:middle line:84%
You celebrate the
birth of a baby

00:35:08.590 --> 00:35:11.230 align:middle line:84%
on the eighth day, no matter
what holiday or event might

00:35:11.230 --> 00:35:12.387 align:middle line:90%
be taking place.

00:35:12.387 --> 00:35:13.720 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: So it's about the birth.

00:35:13.720 --> 00:35:15.430 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: We privilege
life over death.

00:35:15.430 --> 00:35:17.050 align:middle line:84%
We privilege light
over darkness.

00:35:17.050 --> 00:35:17.470 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: That's beautiful.

00:35:17.470 --> 00:35:19.840 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: We don't allow
the darkness to eclipse.

00:35:19.840 --> 00:35:22.450 align:middle line:84%
You know, your thumb
can blot out the sun.

00:35:22.450 --> 00:35:23.902 align:middle line:90%
Think about that for a moment.

00:35:23.902 --> 00:35:26.110 align:middle line:84%
But that doesn't mean you
should give more importance

00:35:26.110 --> 00:35:28.140 align:middle line:90%
to the thumb than the sun.

00:35:28.140 --> 00:35:29.160 align:middle line:90%
It's perspective.

00:35:29.160 --> 00:35:30.580 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And it doesn't
mean the sun is small.

00:35:30.580 --> 00:35:31.420 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: Correct.

00:35:31.420 --> 00:35:33.420 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: But then, why do
you think that death is

00:35:33.420 --> 00:35:36.292 align:middle line:90%
the number one fear of people?

00:35:36.292 --> 00:35:38.500 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: Well, I think people
fear death because they

00:35:38.500 --> 00:35:40.330 align:middle line:90%
don't know much about it.

00:35:40.330 --> 00:35:41.548 align:middle line:90%
And I think they fear death--

00:35:41.548 --> 00:35:43.090 align:middle line:84%
their fear of death
is really, if you

00:35:43.090 --> 00:35:49.380 align:middle line:84%
think about it, a reflection of
how much they love life, right?

00:35:49.380 --> 00:35:50.630 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right, the loss of it.

00:35:50.630 --> 00:35:53.360 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: You wouldn't fear
death if you didn't love

00:35:53.360 --> 00:35:55.380 align:middle line:90%
life so terribly much, right?

00:35:55.380 --> 00:35:56.180 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yeah.

00:35:56.180 --> 00:36:00.380 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: So first of all, I
don't think it predominates.

00:36:00.380 --> 00:36:04.220 align:middle line:84%
I think it's the symptom
of a love of life

00:36:04.220 --> 00:36:06.590 align:middle line:90%
more than a symptom of fear.

00:36:06.590 --> 00:36:10.790 align:middle line:84%
But people who fear death
haven't seen much of it

00:36:10.790 --> 00:36:13.270 align:middle line:84%
up close the way I
have, or maybe you have.

00:36:13.270 --> 00:36:16.580 align:middle line:84%
I've held the hands-- and
I'm not exaggerating here--

00:36:16.580 --> 00:36:20.900 align:middle line:90%
of close to 1,000 dying people.

00:36:20.900 --> 00:36:25.100 align:middle line:84%
Not one time, not
once in 31 years,

00:36:25.100 --> 00:36:27.740 align:middle line:90%
when a person is really dying--

00:36:27.740 --> 00:36:29.210 align:middle line:84%
I don't mean
thinking about dying.

00:36:29.210 --> 00:36:30.752 align:middle line:84%
I don't mean you've
got a few months.

00:36:30.752 --> 00:36:31.585 align:middle line:90%
I mean really dying.

00:36:31.585 --> 00:36:32.502 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Transitioning.

00:36:32.502 --> 00:36:34.750 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: Not one time has
that person been afraid.

00:36:34.750 --> 00:36:35.550 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Wow.

00:36:35.550 --> 00:36:37.680 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: It is
nothing but peace.

00:36:37.680 --> 00:36:38.480 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Really?

00:36:38.480 --> 00:36:41.395 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: And if people
really knew that,

00:36:41.395 --> 00:36:42.770 align:middle line:84%
they wouldn't fear
death so much.

00:36:42.770 --> 00:36:44.437 align:middle line:84%
Now, how do I deal
with that with people

00:36:44.437 --> 00:36:46.130 align:middle line:90%
when I'm counseling?

00:36:46.130 --> 00:36:48.590 align:middle line:90%
Look, this is the truth.

00:36:48.590 --> 00:36:52.440 align:middle line:84%
If you are worried about
dying, it's not your day.

00:36:52.440 --> 00:36:53.240 align:middle line:90%
It's not.

00:36:53.240 --> 00:36:55.250 align:middle line:90%
Anxiety is for the living.

00:36:55.250 --> 00:36:56.240 align:middle line:90%
It really is.

00:36:56.240 --> 00:36:59.030 align:middle line:84%
People who are really
dying, they're not afraid,

00:36:59.030 --> 00:37:00.970 align:middle line:90%
and they're not anxious.

00:37:00.970 --> 00:37:04.820 align:middle line:84%
And I think if people
knew this, really knew it,

00:37:04.820 --> 00:37:06.700 align:middle line:84%
they would calm
down a little bit.

00:37:06.700 --> 00:37:08.920 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Yet, you go
through so much suffering

00:37:08.920 --> 00:37:15.840 align:middle line:84%
if you're ill and pain before
death and failure of the body.

00:37:15.840 --> 00:37:16.640 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: Yes.

00:37:16.640 --> 00:37:18.560 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yet, dying is peaceful?

00:37:18.560 --> 00:37:23.270 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: Yes, because the
disease, whatever it has,

00:37:23.270 --> 00:37:26.370 align:middle line:84%
its own rhythm and power,
its own trajectory.

00:37:26.370 --> 00:37:28.760 align:middle line:90%
And it prepares you.

00:37:28.760 --> 00:37:31.800 align:middle line:84%
It prepares you to let go, and
it prepares your loved ones

00:37:31.800 --> 00:37:32.600 align:middle line:90%
to let go.

00:37:32.600 --> 00:37:37.250 align:middle line:84%
My father-- I haven't talked
about this on camera yet.

00:37:37.250 --> 00:37:41.360 align:middle line:84%
My father died two weeks
ago after 10 years with

00:37:41.360 --> 00:37:44.030 align:middle line:90%
Alzheimer's.

00:37:44.030 --> 00:37:47.480 align:middle line:84%
And when this all began 10
years ago with that diagnosis,

00:37:47.480 --> 00:37:49.670 align:middle line:84%
if you had asked
me, will you ever be

00:37:49.670 --> 00:37:53.940 align:middle line:84%
grateful for the day your father
dies, I would have said no.

00:37:53.940 --> 00:37:59.320 align:middle line:84%
But my father died two weeks
ago peacefully in his sleep,

00:37:59.320 --> 00:38:01.400 align:middle line:90%
and I was deeply grateful.

00:38:01.400 --> 00:38:05.390 align:middle line:84%
Because death came to my
father as a peaceful friend.

00:38:05.390 --> 00:38:08.530 align:middle line:10%
There are many things
worse than dying--

00:38:08.530 --> 00:38:10.370 align:middle line:10%
many.

00:38:10.370 --> 00:38:15.150 align:middle line:84%
And being that ill
is one of them.

00:38:15.150 --> 00:38:18.800 align:middle line:84%
And so this is a hard
thing to understand

00:38:18.800 --> 00:38:22.850 align:middle line:84%
until you've lived it yourself
or through a loved one,

00:38:22.850 --> 00:38:26.510 align:middle line:84%
but death is not
something I fear.

00:38:26.510 --> 00:38:29.090 align:middle line:90%
I fear running out of life.

00:38:29.090 --> 00:38:30.020 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right.

00:38:30.020 --> 00:38:32.600 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: But I don't fear dying.

00:38:32.600 --> 00:38:33.710 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: I don't, either.

00:38:33.710 --> 00:38:37.670 align:middle line:84%
But your father and the fact
that he did pass peacefully,

00:38:37.670 --> 00:38:39.260 align:middle line:90%
does that help you?

00:38:39.260 --> 00:38:40.580 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: Very much.

00:38:40.580 --> 00:38:43.020 align:middle line:84%
And I know, because of
what I do for a living,

00:38:43.020 --> 00:38:45.122 align:middle line:90%
it could have been otherwise.

00:38:45.122 --> 00:38:46.580 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Were you
there at his side?

00:38:46.580 --> 00:38:47.380 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: I was not.

00:38:47.380 --> 00:38:49.640 align:middle line:84%
I got the phone call
at 11:30 at night

00:38:49.640 --> 00:38:55.400 align:middle line:84%
at a friend's 60th birthday
party, standing in her backyard

00:38:55.400 --> 00:38:56.815 align:middle line:90%
with my wife.

00:38:56.815 --> 00:38:58.940 align:middle line:84%
And you know, these are
things that are always just

00:38:58.940 --> 00:39:01.200 align:middle line:84%
around the corner, but
never seem to happen.

00:39:01.200 --> 00:39:02.213 align:middle line:90%
And then they do.

00:39:02.213 --> 00:39:04.130 align:middle line:84%
It's been a very interesting
experience for me

00:39:04.130 --> 00:39:07.310 align:middle line:84%
to go through this
death, not as the rabbi,

00:39:07.310 --> 00:39:11.960 align:middle line:84%
but as the son of this
complicated and extraordinary

00:39:11.960 --> 00:39:14.062 align:middle line:90%
man.

00:39:14.062 --> 00:39:15.020 align:middle line:90%
And I've learned a lot.

00:39:15.020 --> 00:39:16.460 align:middle line:90%
Maybe it'll be the next book.

00:39:16.460 --> 00:39:18.880 align:middle line:84%
There's something about
vicarious experience

00:39:18.880 --> 00:39:21.130 align:middle line:84%
and then the real experience
that always interests me.

00:39:21.130 --> 00:39:22.588 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: You seem
to do this a lot.

00:39:22.588 --> 00:39:23.630 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: Yeah, it's true.

00:39:23.630 --> 00:39:25.297 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: To really
want to experience it.

00:39:25.297 --> 00:39:27.410 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: But I have
never met a person who's

00:39:27.410 --> 00:39:30.020 align:middle line:84%
dying who is afraid,
and I've met many.

00:39:30.020 --> 00:39:32.450 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: That is incredible
for you to say that

00:39:32.450 --> 00:39:36.120 align:middle line:84%
and so reassuring
for you to say that.

00:39:36.120 --> 00:39:38.900 align:middle line:84%
And when somebody goes
through that type of thing,

00:39:38.900 --> 00:39:41.250 align:middle line:84%
like an Alzheimer's
or the loved ones,

00:39:41.250 --> 00:39:44.540 align:middle line:84%
the people that are
dealing with that,

00:39:44.540 --> 00:39:47.330 align:middle line:84%
there are many
death-like moments.

00:39:47.330 --> 00:39:48.580 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: Well, they die twice.

00:39:48.580 --> 00:39:49.380 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes.

00:39:49.380 --> 00:39:50.550 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: It's really true.

00:39:50.550 --> 00:39:52.310 align:middle line:84%
You know, people
with these kinds

00:39:52.310 --> 00:39:55.550 align:middle line:84%
of diseases all under
this umbrella of dementia,

00:39:55.550 --> 00:39:56.480 align:middle line:90%
they die twice.

00:39:56.480 --> 00:39:58.250 align:middle line:90%
You lose them twice.

00:39:58.250 --> 00:40:01.310 align:middle line:84%
And the pain is
laddered out in doses

00:40:01.310 --> 00:40:03.690 align:middle line:84%
over a period of, in
my case, a decade.

00:40:03.690 --> 00:40:05.690 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: You have to learn
how to deal with that.

00:40:05.690 --> 00:40:06.607 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: Well, you do.

00:40:06.607 --> 00:40:07.760 align:middle line:90%
It's a weaning process.

00:40:07.760 --> 00:40:10.790 align:middle line:84%
The disease weans you
from your loved one.

00:40:10.790 --> 00:40:13.850 align:middle line:84%
And I will say, at least
in my father's case,

00:40:13.850 --> 00:40:18.500 align:middle line:84%
that the disease came with its
own appropriately measured dose

00:40:18.500 --> 00:40:20.115 align:middle line:90%
of anesthesia.

00:40:20.115 --> 00:40:20.990 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: For everyone?

00:40:20.990 --> 00:40:23.270 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: For
everyone and for him.

00:40:23.270 --> 00:40:27.320 align:middle line:84%
You know, he mostly didn't
know that he didn't know.

00:40:27.320 --> 00:40:29.900 align:middle line:84%
I also felt this way going
through the funeral, which

00:40:29.900 --> 00:40:31.160 align:middle line:90%
is quite surreal.

00:40:31.160 --> 00:40:32.118 align:middle line:90%
And I eulogized my dad.

00:40:32.118 --> 00:40:32.918 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: You did?

00:40:32.918 --> 00:40:35.300 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: I was just not going
to let anyone else do that.

00:40:35.300 --> 00:40:39.080 align:middle line:84%
I felt honored, and
I know it's what

00:40:39.080 --> 00:40:40.880 align:middle line:90%
he would have expected of me.

00:40:40.880 --> 00:40:42.470 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: How was that for you?

00:40:42.470 --> 00:40:43.575 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: Surreal.

00:40:43.575 --> 00:40:44.390 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Of course.

00:40:44.390 --> 00:40:46.180 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: Beautiful.

00:40:46.180 --> 00:40:47.320 align:middle line:90%
An honor.

00:40:47.320 --> 00:40:49.430 align:middle line:90%
A privilege.

00:40:49.430 --> 00:40:51.190 align:middle line:84%
But I would say
that this experience

00:40:51.190 --> 00:40:53.200 align:middle line:84%
of eulogizing my
father and placing

00:40:53.200 --> 00:40:57.040 align:middle line:84%
those shovelfuls of earth
on his plain pine casket

00:40:57.040 --> 00:41:01.290 align:middle line:84%
also came with their
own dose of anesthesia.

00:41:01.290 --> 00:41:03.400 align:middle line:84%
We somehow protect
ourselves as we

00:41:03.400 --> 00:41:05.590 align:middle line:84%
go through these intense
emotional experiences,

00:41:05.590 --> 00:41:07.690 align:middle line:90%
and I was grateful for that.

00:41:07.690 --> 00:41:09.570 align:middle line:84%
I was as present as
I was able to be.

00:41:09.570 --> 00:41:11.320 align:middle line:84%
I didn't want to be
more present, frankly.

00:41:11.320 --> 00:41:14.260 align:middle line:90%


00:41:14.260 --> 00:41:17.410 align:middle line:90%
But I don't think there's any--

00:41:17.410 --> 00:41:20.260 align:middle line:84%
I know there's no
way through life

00:41:20.260 --> 00:41:23.770 align:middle line:84%
without walking through
these difficult experiences.

00:41:23.770 --> 00:41:26.620 align:middle line:84%
And my point in this
book is that you do not

00:41:26.620 --> 00:41:29.860 align:middle line:84%
have to come out of
them a lesser person.

00:41:29.860 --> 00:41:34.910 align:middle line:84%
You come out of them a greater,
more spiritual, more beautiful

00:41:34.910 --> 00:41:35.710 align:middle line:90%
person.

00:41:35.710 --> 00:41:39.010 align:middle line:84%
That's why I called it "More
Beautiful Than Before."

00:41:39.010 --> 00:41:42.440 align:middle line:84%
And suffering is the
transformational component.

00:41:42.440 --> 00:41:44.373 align:middle line:90%
There's no other way.

00:41:44.373 --> 00:41:45.790 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Well, the
Jewish tradition

00:41:45.790 --> 00:41:49.760 align:middle line:84%
has a wonderful way of honoring
the transition of a loved one.

00:41:49.760 --> 00:41:50.760 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: Yes, very true.

00:41:50.760 --> 00:41:52.010 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: It's in Shiva.

00:41:52.010 --> 00:41:52.810 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: Yes.

00:41:52.810 --> 00:41:55.840 align:middle line:84%
So Judaism-- the
rabbis were very wise.

00:41:55.840 --> 00:41:59.470 align:middle line:84%
You know, sometimes laws are
created to limit and control

00:41:59.470 --> 00:42:00.700 align:middle line:90%
human behavior.

00:42:00.700 --> 00:42:03.340 align:middle line:84%
And sometimes they're
created in response

00:42:03.340 --> 00:42:06.820 align:middle line:84%
to what human behavior
requires, what we need.

00:42:06.820 --> 00:42:08.630 align:middle line:84%
The laws of mourning
in Judaism--

00:42:08.630 --> 00:42:10.750 align:middle line:84%
so clearly, from
my perspective--

00:42:10.750 --> 00:42:14.380 align:middle line:84%
were designed to support
people and scaffold them

00:42:14.380 --> 00:42:18.220 align:middle line:84%
during this time of intense
emotional, and sometimes

00:42:18.220 --> 00:42:19.820 align:middle line:90%
physical, need.

00:42:19.820 --> 00:42:22.660 align:middle line:84%
So the first three days
are called, in Hebrew,

00:42:22.660 --> 00:42:24.490 align:middle line:84%
[SPEAKING HEBREW]----
days of weeping.

00:42:24.490 --> 00:42:25.450 align:middle line:90%
All you do is weep.

00:42:25.450 --> 00:42:26.590 align:middle line:90%
That's all.

00:42:26.590 --> 00:42:29.290 align:middle line:84%
You have no responsibilities
and no obligations

00:42:29.290 --> 00:42:31.150 align:middle line:84%
other than to curl
up in a ball and cry

00:42:31.150 --> 00:42:33.730 align:middle line:90%
if that's what you want to do.

00:42:33.730 --> 00:42:36.310 align:middle line:84%
The first seven days
after the burial

00:42:36.310 --> 00:42:39.130 align:middle line:84%
are called Shiva, which is
the Hebrew word for seven.

00:42:39.130 --> 00:42:43.060 align:middle line:84%
And during that
period, you stay home.

00:42:43.060 --> 00:42:45.100 align:middle line:90%
You hunker down.

00:42:45.100 --> 00:42:48.055 align:middle line:84%
The community is
supposed to provide food.

00:42:48.055 --> 00:42:50.680 align:middle line:84%
There is a prayer service in the
morning and one in the evening

00:42:50.680 --> 00:42:53.350 align:middle line:84%
when you're surrounded by
friends and family who remember

00:42:53.350 --> 00:42:54.820 align:middle line:90%
and who care.

00:42:54.820 --> 00:42:58.540 align:middle line:84%
And you just allow the
community to hold you.

00:42:58.540 --> 00:43:00.700 align:middle line:84%
And I'll tell you
something quite beautiful

00:43:00.700 --> 00:43:03.640 align:middle line:84%
that I do talk
about in the book.

00:43:03.640 --> 00:43:06.550 align:middle line:84%
Many years ago,
I was at a Shiva,

00:43:06.550 --> 00:43:09.160 align:middle line:84%
leading the service for a man
whose 30-year-old daughter was

00:43:09.160 --> 00:43:11.620 align:middle line:90%
killed in a car accident.

00:43:11.620 --> 00:43:14.260 align:middle line:84%
There we were that evening in
the service, and at the end,

00:43:14.260 --> 00:43:16.780 align:middle line:84%
we all had our arms around each
other, and we were singing.

00:43:16.780 --> 00:43:19.790 align:middle line:84%
And he looked around this
circle, and he turned to me

00:43:19.790 --> 00:43:22.870 align:middle line:84%
and he said, this
changes nothing,

00:43:22.870 --> 00:43:25.817 align:middle line:90%
but it means everything.

00:43:25.817 --> 00:43:27.650 align:middle line:84%
And I'd never heard it
put more beautifully.

00:43:27.650 --> 00:43:29.100 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: That is beautiful.

00:43:29.100 --> 00:43:32.620 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: So this seven
days changes nothing,

00:43:32.620 --> 00:43:34.392 align:middle line:90%
and it means everything.

00:43:34.392 --> 00:43:36.100 align:middle line:84%
And by the way, there
are all these rules

00:43:36.100 --> 00:43:36.820 align:middle line:90%
about how to behave.

00:43:36.820 --> 00:43:38.612 align:middle line:84%
You're not supposed to
approach the mourner

00:43:38.612 --> 00:43:39.700 align:middle line:90%
unless they summon you.

00:43:39.700 --> 00:43:41.770 align:middle line:84%
If they do, you're not
allowed to distract them

00:43:41.770 --> 00:43:43.452 align:middle line:90%
from talking about their grief.

00:43:43.452 --> 00:43:45.160 align:middle line:84%
You know, that's our
natural inclination.

00:43:45.160 --> 00:43:46.270 align:middle line:90%
How about those Dodgers, right?

00:43:46.270 --> 00:43:46.810 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right.

00:43:46.810 --> 00:43:47.830 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: That's wrong.

00:43:47.830 --> 00:43:49.057 align:middle line:90%
They want to talk about it.

00:43:49.057 --> 00:43:50.140 align:middle line:90%
They want to hear stories.

00:43:50.140 --> 00:43:51.580 align:middle line:90%
They want to cry.

00:43:51.580 --> 00:43:55.150 align:middle line:84%
They need to, and you have
to be sensitive to that

00:43:55.150 --> 00:43:58.030 align:middle line:84%
and dial into that
frequency that they're on.

00:43:58.030 --> 00:44:01.170 align:middle line:84%
And then the first 30 days
is a whole other period

00:44:01.170 --> 00:44:05.230 align:middle line:84%
of refrain from doing all kinds
of things, normal activities.

00:44:05.230 --> 00:44:08.320 align:middle line:84%
And for the first year,
you don't go to parties.

00:44:08.320 --> 00:44:11.350 align:middle line:84%
You don't have to be around
music and dancing now people.

00:44:11.350 --> 00:44:13.810 align:middle line:84%
Now, people misunderstand
this prohibition.

00:44:13.810 --> 00:44:16.370 align:middle line:84%
They think, well, it's seen as
disrespectful to the deceased

00:44:16.370 --> 00:44:17.380 align:middle line:90%
if you're partying.

00:44:17.380 --> 00:44:18.490 align:middle line:90%
Wrong.

00:44:18.490 --> 00:44:21.880 align:middle line:84%
It's because during that first
year of grief, for many people,

00:44:21.880 --> 00:44:24.805 align:middle line:84%
it's so difficult to
be around happy people.

00:44:24.805 --> 00:44:26.180 align:middle line:84%
You don't want to
be around them.

00:44:26.180 --> 00:44:27.410 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: But wouldn't it
help you feel better?

00:44:27.410 --> 00:44:29.380 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: No, it
makes you feel worse,

00:44:29.380 --> 00:44:31.060 align:middle line:90%
because you can't connect.

00:44:31.060 --> 00:44:32.487 align:middle line:90%
You feel isolated.

00:44:32.487 --> 00:44:34.570 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: But it gives you
an option to feel better.

00:44:34.570 --> 00:44:36.362 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: You have the
option, but you don't

00:44:36.362 --> 00:44:37.850 align:middle line:90%
have to expose yourself to it.

00:44:37.850 --> 00:44:38.650 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: It depends.

00:44:38.650 --> 00:44:40.442 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: Not everyone's
built the same way.

00:44:40.442 --> 00:44:43.030 align:middle line:90%
But it gives you permission--

00:44:43.030 --> 00:44:45.640 align:middle line:90%
permission-- to take your time.

00:44:45.640 --> 00:44:48.250 align:middle line:84%
People come to see me
sometimes three or four months

00:44:48.250 --> 00:44:51.100 align:middle line:84%
after a death and say, Rabbi,
my kids are worried about me.

00:44:51.100 --> 00:44:52.480 align:middle line:90%
I don't want to date.

00:44:52.480 --> 00:44:55.285 align:middle line:90%
I don't feel like doing much.

00:44:55.285 --> 00:44:56.660 align:middle line:84%
Is there something
wrong with me?

00:44:56.660 --> 00:44:59.020 align:middle line:84%
And I said, no, there's
something wrong with your kids.

00:44:59.020 --> 00:45:01.330 align:middle line:90%
Three or four months is nothing.

00:45:01.330 --> 00:45:02.950 align:middle line:84%
You spent 60 years
with the woman

00:45:02.950 --> 00:45:05.620 align:middle line:84%
of your life and your
dreams, and they expect

00:45:05.620 --> 00:45:06.950 align:middle line:90%
you to move on in four months?

00:45:06.950 --> 00:45:09.460 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: But what about
celebrating their life,

00:45:09.460 --> 00:45:10.450 align:middle line:90%
celebrating their life?

00:45:10.450 --> 00:45:14.140 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: I prefer honoring.

00:45:14.140 --> 00:45:21.010 align:middle line:84%
To ask someone to
celebrate is cruel

00:45:21.010 --> 00:45:24.100 align:middle line:84%
when they're feeling that
kind of intense pain.

00:45:24.100 --> 00:45:25.720 align:middle line:84%
You know, a slap on
the back, come on,

00:45:25.720 --> 00:45:27.678 align:middle line:90%
get over it is not appropriate.

00:45:27.678 --> 00:45:28.720 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: That's different.

00:45:28.720 --> 00:45:29.520 align:middle line:90%
That is different.

00:45:29.520 --> 00:45:30.820 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: It's not appropriate.

00:45:30.820 --> 00:45:33.205 align:middle line:84%
I prefer honoring
a person's life.

00:45:33.205 --> 00:45:34.330 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Like your father's.

00:45:34.330 --> 00:45:37.840 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: Like my father's,
both of his lives--

00:45:37.840 --> 00:45:41.050 align:middle line:84%
the one before the
Alzheimer's and the one after.

00:45:41.050 --> 00:45:42.820 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: That's a
great distinction.

00:45:42.820 --> 00:45:46.220 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: Yes, because he was two
different people, in many ways.

00:45:46.220 --> 00:45:50.480 align:middle line:84%
But this idea of giving
ourselves enough time and space

00:45:50.480 --> 00:45:52.610 align:middle line:90%
and permission to grieve--

00:45:52.610 --> 00:45:56.120 align:middle line:84%
extremely important in this
world of hurry up and get it

00:45:56.120 --> 00:45:57.652 align:middle line:90%
over with.

00:45:57.652 --> 00:45:58.860 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: That's a great point.

00:45:58.860 --> 00:46:02.500 align:middle line:84%
I was looking up the
root word of patience,

00:46:02.500 --> 00:46:07.670 align:middle line:90%
and that pati- means suffering.

00:46:07.670 --> 00:46:09.920 align:middle line:90%
It's the root of suffering.

00:46:09.920 --> 00:46:13.060 align:middle line:84%
And I was equating
when one is patient,

00:46:13.060 --> 00:46:17.660 align:middle line:84%
you're just prolonging or being
tolerant of the suffering.

00:46:17.660 --> 00:46:20.930 align:middle line:84%
And that's what the
word "patience" means.

00:46:20.930 --> 00:46:23.458 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: Well, to be
patient or be a patient

00:46:23.458 --> 00:46:24.500 align:middle line:90%
are two different things.

00:46:24.500 --> 00:46:25.560 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right.

00:46:25.560 --> 00:46:26.360 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: Right?

00:46:26.360 --> 00:46:27.470 align:middle line:90%
So let's not forget that.

00:46:27.470 --> 00:46:28.030 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: It's the same
word, the same root.

00:46:28.030 --> 00:46:29.738 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: There's a
noun and an adjective,

00:46:29.738 --> 00:46:32.720 align:middle line:84%
but nouns and adjectives
are not the same thing.

00:46:32.720 --> 00:46:35.480 align:middle line:84%
To be a patient is
to definitionally

00:46:35.480 --> 00:46:37.820 align:middle line:90%
be in some form of suffering.

00:46:37.820 --> 00:46:41.690 align:middle line:84%
To be patient can be a
form of suffering, right?

00:46:41.690 --> 00:46:45.200 align:middle line:90%


00:46:45.200 --> 00:46:50.600 align:middle line:84%
A way to think of it
is, how does one endure

00:46:50.600 --> 00:46:52.040 align:middle line:90%
that period of suffering?

00:46:52.040 --> 00:46:58.580 align:middle line:84%
Can you endure it with some
degree of equanimity, of grace,

00:46:58.580 --> 00:47:01.400 align:middle line:90%
of quiet strength?

00:47:01.400 --> 00:47:05.300 align:middle line:84%
And that's a form of
patience, of tolerance.

00:47:05.300 --> 00:47:08.730 align:middle line:84%
In Hebrew, the word for
tolerance and patience--

00:47:08.730 --> 00:47:10.850 align:middle line:84%
I-E-N-C-E, patience
and tolerance--

00:47:10.850 --> 00:47:13.010 align:middle line:90%
come from the same root.

00:47:13.010 --> 00:47:16.880 align:middle line:84%
So to be patient is
also to be tolerant,

00:47:16.880 --> 00:47:20.780 align:middle line:84%
to tolerate something, to
withstand it, to take it.

00:47:20.780 --> 00:47:23.640 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: To tolerate
suffering, also, in many ways.

00:47:23.640 --> 00:47:24.440 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: Yes.

00:47:24.440 --> 00:47:25.565 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: That's interesting.

00:47:25.565 --> 00:47:28.550 align:middle line:84%
Yet, you bring such a
lightness to your congregation

00:47:28.550 --> 00:47:30.155 align:middle line:90%
through the music, through the--

00:47:30.155 --> 00:47:31.280 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: Yeah, we have fun.

