00:50:52.240 --> 00:50:53.140 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: That's great.

00:50:53.140 --> 00:50:54.840 align:middle line:84%
It looks like you
have so much fun.

00:50:54.840 --> 00:50:55.677 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: Have to.

00:50:55.677 --> 00:50:56.510 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes, you do.

00:50:56.510 --> 00:50:57.780 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: What's the
point, you know,

00:50:57.780 --> 00:50:58.905 align:middle line:90%
if you can't have some fun.

00:50:58.905 --> 00:51:01.640 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: We're talking so much
about suffering and pain here.

00:51:01.640 --> 00:51:06.010 align:middle line:84%
But there are some things that
you have talked about openly

00:51:06.010 --> 00:51:09.190 align:middle line:84%
to say and not to say
when someone is dealing

00:51:09.190 --> 00:51:11.867 align:middle line:90%
with a severe situation.

00:51:11.867 --> 00:51:12.700 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: Yeah, yeah.

00:51:12.700 --> 00:51:14.330 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Especially the
loss of a loved one.

00:51:14.330 --> 00:51:15.130 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: Yeah.

00:51:15.130 --> 00:51:17.140 align:middle line:84%
Well, first of all, what
you say and don't say

00:51:17.140 --> 00:51:20.050 align:middle line:84%
is not nearly as important
as walking in the door.

00:51:20.050 --> 00:51:20.922 align:middle line:90%
Show up.

00:51:20.922 --> 00:51:21.880 align:middle line:90%
That's the first thing.

00:51:21.880 --> 00:51:24.047 align:middle line:84%
I have people call me and
say, Rabbi, my best friend

00:51:24.047 --> 00:51:26.560 align:middle line:84%
from college with just diagnosed
with pancreatic cancer.

00:51:26.560 --> 00:51:28.000 align:middle line:90%
I'm flying back to New York.

00:51:28.000 --> 00:51:29.260 align:middle line:90%
What do I say?

00:51:29.260 --> 00:51:31.480 align:middle line:84%
And my answer is always,
it doesn't matter.

00:51:31.480 --> 00:51:32.950 align:middle line:90%
You walk in the door.

00:51:32.950 --> 00:51:34.020 align:middle line:90%
The rest will unfold.

00:51:34.020 --> 00:51:35.770 align:middle line:84%
You know, even after
all these years, when

00:51:35.770 --> 00:51:37.228 align:middle line:84%
I'm in the hallway
at the hospital,

00:51:37.228 --> 00:51:38.950 align:middle line:84%
before I walk in
the room, I don't

00:51:38.950 --> 00:51:41.270 align:middle line:90%
know what I'm going to say.

00:51:41.270 --> 00:51:44.127 align:middle line:84%
All I know is I have to walk
through that threshold--

00:51:44.127 --> 00:51:44.960 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: To be there.

00:51:44.960 --> 00:51:45.610 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: --into that door.

00:51:45.610 --> 00:51:46.270 align:middle line:90%
Show up.

00:51:46.270 --> 00:51:47.228 align:middle line:90%
That's the first thing.

00:51:47.228 --> 00:51:50.800 align:middle line:84%
Now, what not to
say-- so important.

00:51:50.800 --> 00:51:53.740 align:middle line:84%
I tell people never
say these seven words.

00:51:53.740 --> 00:51:57.310 align:middle line:10%
Never say these seven words
to someone who's suffering--

00:51:57.310 --> 00:52:00.550 align:middle line:10%
let me know if
you need anything.

00:52:00.550 --> 00:52:04.540 align:middle line:84%
That is the worst thing you can
say, and so many people say it.

00:52:04.540 --> 00:52:07.360 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: I can't tell you how
many times I had said that

00:52:07.360 --> 00:52:08.560 align:middle line:90%
prior to reading your book.

00:52:08.560 --> 00:52:11.102 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: What does that do, let
me know if you need anything?

00:52:11.102 --> 00:52:14.110 align:middle line:84%
First of all, it places
the responsibility back

00:52:14.110 --> 00:52:16.610 align:middle line:84%
onto the shoulders of the
person who is already suffering.

00:52:16.610 --> 00:52:17.200 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Grieving, yes.

00:52:17.200 --> 00:52:18.033 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: Number one.

00:52:18.033 --> 00:52:20.980 align:middle line:84%
Number two, most people don't
mean it when they say it.

00:52:20.980 --> 00:52:24.190 align:middle line:84%
Number three, even
if they do mean it,

00:52:24.190 --> 00:52:26.320 align:middle line:90%
you're not going to do it.

00:52:26.320 --> 00:52:28.190 align:middle line:84%
The sufferer is not
going to do that.

00:52:28.190 --> 00:52:30.790 align:middle line:84%
They have enough to deal
with in their own darkness.

00:52:30.790 --> 00:52:31.960 align:middle line:90%
Never say it.

00:52:31.960 --> 00:52:32.800 align:middle line:90%
It's fake.

00:52:32.800 --> 00:52:33.850 align:middle line:90%
It's fake empathy.

00:52:33.850 --> 00:52:35.350 align:middle line:90%
It's kabuki empathy.

00:52:35.350 --> 00:52:37.910 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Nobody is in that
place of suffering that says,

00:52:37.910 --> 00:52:39.370 align:middle line:90%
oh, I need this.

00:52:39.370 --> 00:52:40.130 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: They may
know what they need.

00:52:40.130 --> 00:52:41.588 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Who's going
to think of it?

00:52:41.588 --> 00:52:45.820 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: Don't ask someone let
me know, tell me what you need.

00:52:45.820 --> 00:52:48.490 align:middle line:90%
Figure it out.

00:52:48.490 --> 00:52:50.740 align:middle line:84%
Imagine yourself
in their situation.

00:52:50.740 --> 00:52:53.180 align:middle line:84%
Think about what would be
helpful to you, and do it.

00:52:53.180 --> 00:52:54.430 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: So what would that be?

00:52:54.430 --> 00:52:57.010 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: Carpooling the kids,
play dates for the kids,

00:52:57.010 --> 00:52:59.770 align:middle line:84%
a meal dropped off
at the front door,

00:52:59.770 --> 00:53:04.900 align:middle line:84%
going with to the doctor's
appointments to take notes,

00:53:04.900 --> 00:53:06.770 align:middle line:84%
hooking them up with
Netflix, whatever.

00:53:06.770 --> 00:53:07.570 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes.

00:53:07.570 --> 00:53:09.970 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: Whatever it
is, figure it out,

00:53:09.970 --> 00:53:13.313 align:middle line:84%
even if it's just calling
every day or emailing every day

00:53:13.313 --> 00:53:14.230 align:middle line:90%
or just sitting there.

00:53:14.230 --> 00:53:17.110 align:middle line:84%
You know, the Navajo have
this beautiful custom.

00:53:17.110 --> 00:53:19.750 align:middle line:84%
When someone in
the village dies,

00:53:19.750 --> 00:53:24.160 align:middle line:84%
you go to the home of the
mourners, you walk in,

00:53:24.160 --> 00:53:29.230 align:middle line:84%
you sit down, you stay a
while, and then you leave.

00:53:29.230 --> 00:53:30.520 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: You say nothing?

00:53:30.520 --> 00:53:32.470 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: You say nothing.

00:53:32.470 --> 00:53:35.690 align:middle line:90%
Your presence says everything.

00:53:35.690 --> 00:53:38.770 align:middle line:84%
So just take a
walk with someone.

00:53:38.770 --> 00:53:40.330 align:middle line:90%
Let's go for a walk.

00:53:40.330 --> 00:53:42.220 align:middle line:90%
Whatever it is, figure it out.

00:53:42.220 --> 00:53:45.070 align:middle line:90%
And even if you're wrong--

00:53:45.070 --> 00:53:47.260 align:middle line:84%
she sent me six
pints of ice cream,

00:53:47.260 --> 00:53:48.700 align:middle line:90%
and I'm lactose intolerant.

00:53:48.700 --> 00:53:49.740 align:middle line:90%
Even if you're wrong--

00:53:49.740 --> 00:53:50.440 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: It's the
thought that counts.

00:53:50.440 --> 00:53:52.315 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: --the thought
really is what counts,

00:53:52.315 --> 00:53:54.463 align:middle line:84%
and the gesture
will be remembered.

00:53:54.463 --> 00:53:55.630 align:middle line:90%
That is the important thing.

00:53:55.630 --> 00:53:58.150 align:middle line:84%
But never say, let me
know if you need anything.

00:53:58.150 --> 00:54:00.730 align:middle line:84%
And I'll tell you how
pervasive this is.

00:54:00.730 --> 00:54:04.180 align:middle line:84%
I mentioned earlier that I
just went through the death

00:54:04.180 --> 00:54:05.770 align:middle line:90%
of my father two weeks ago.

00:54:05.770 --> 00:54:09.820 align:middle line:84%
My congregation has heard
me say, never say, let me

00:54:09.820 --> 00:54:12.717 align:middle line:84%
know if you need
anything many times.

00:54:12.717 --> 00:54:14.050 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: They all said it to you.

00:54:14.050 --> 00:54:16.217 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: A huge percentage
of the emails and letters

00:54:16.217 --> 00:54:19.000 align:middle line:84%
and cards I've
received said, please,

00:54:19.000 --> 00:54:22.480 align:middle line:84%
don't hesitate to let me
know if you need anything.

00:54:22.480 --> 00:54:25.006 align:middle line:84%
It's a hard message
to get through.

00:54:25.006 --> 00:54:26.740 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Yes, but
I listened to it,

00:54:26.740 --> 00:54:28.668 align:middle line:90%
and I've not said it since then.

00:54:28.668 --> 00:54:29.960 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: I'm glad to hear that.

00:54:29.960 --> 00:54:32.530 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And then, when I do
have a friend or anyone who's

00:54:32.530 --> 00:54:35.303 align:middle line:84%
going through that,
we'll make a list of,

00:54:35.303 --> 00:54:36.470 align:middle line:90%
these are things you can do.

00:54:36.470 --> 00:54:37.928 align:middle line:84%
And if you're going
to have a meal,

00:54:37.928 --> 00:54:40.010 align:middle line:84%
make sure you include
the silverware.

00:54:40.010 --> 00:54:40.810 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: Yes.

00:54:40.810 --> 00:54:42.800 align:middle line:84%
And by the way, containers
they don't have to return,

00:54:42.800 --> 00:54:45.030 align:middle line:84%
which gives them another
job they don't need, right?

00:54:45.030 --> 00:54:46.810 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: There's
a lot to it, yes.

00:54:46.810 --> 00:54:48.880 align:middle line:84%
In terms of suffering,
there are those

00:54:48.880 --> 00:54:50.980 align:middle line:84%
that are also suffering
because they've

00:54:50.980 --> 00:54:53.330 align:middle line:90%
caused other people to suffer.

00:54:53.330 --> 00:54:54.130 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: Yes.

00:54:54.130 --> 00:54:55.870 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And they
carry that burden.

00:54:55.870 --> 00:54:56.290 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: Yes.

00:54:56.290 --> 00:54:57.520 align:middle line:90%
That's its own world of pain.

00:54:57.520 --> 00:54:59.210 align:middle line:84%
And frankly, that's
something in the book.

00:54:59.210 --> 00:55:01.600 align:middle line:84%
I addressed that I could not
find addressed in other books.

00:55:01.600 --> 00:55:03.010 align:middle line:84%
Look, I didn't
create a genre here.

00:55:03.010 --> 00:55:04.593 align:middle line:84%
There are many books
about how to deal

00:55:04.593 --> 00:55:07.540 align:middle line:84%
with certain types of pain--
grief, divorce, chronic pain,

00:55:07.540 --> 00:55:08.560 align:middle line:90%
et cetera.

00:55:08.560 --> 00:55:09.970 align:middle line:84%
There's almost
nothing about what

00:55:09.970 --> 00:55:12.520 align:middle line:84%
do you do when you're
the betrayer, not

00:55:12.520 --> 00:55:15.050 align:middle line:84%
the betrayed, when you're the
perpetrator, not the victim.

00:55:15.050 --> 00:55:15.850 align:middle line:90%
Then what?

00:55:15.850 --> 00:55:22.060 align:middle line:84%
Because believe me, that's its
own world of very deep pain.

00:55:22.060 --> 00:55:25.460 align:middle line:90%
So what do you do?

00:55:25.460 --> 00:55:27.458 align:middle line:90%
The first thing is--

00:55:27.458 --> 00:55:29.500 align:middle line:84%
I talk about this in a
chapter in the book called

00:55:29.500 --> 00:55:35.500 align:middle line:84%
"Hurt and Run," where I had this
very crazy experience of two

00:55:35.500 --> 00:55:37.990 align:middle line:84%
families in the
congregation in one year

00:55:37.990 --> 00:55:40.330 align:middle line:84%
both losing loved
ones who were killed

00:55:40.330 --> 00:55:42.790 align:middle line:90%
as pedestrians by drivers.

00:55:42.790 --> 00:55:45.810 align:middle line:84%
In one case, it
was a hit and run.

00:55:45.810 --> 00:55:48.130 align:middle line:84%
In the other case,
the driver did

00:55:48.130 --> 00:55:53.140 align:middle line:84%
everything possible
to set things right,

00:55:53.140 --> 00:55:55.600 align:middle line:84%
understanding that you
can't bring someone back.

00:55:55.600 --> 00:55:57.670 align:middle line:90%
But she did her very best.

00:55:57.670 --> 00:56:01.060 align:middle line:84%
So I compare and contrast
these two situations.

00:56:01.060 --> 00:56:05.320 align:middle line:84%
And the incredible
unending, unbearable pain

00:56:05.320 --> 00:56:08.110 align:middle line:84%
of hit and run
versus the healing

00:56:08.110 --> 00:56:12.400 align:middle line:84%
that was possible for
accepting responsibility.

00:56:12.400 --> 00:56:16.390 align:middle line:84%
So, first thing, and
most important thing,

00:56:16.390 --> 00:56:20.060 align:middle line:84%
is to be able to utter the
three most difficult words

00:56:20.060 --> 00:56:24.550 align:middle line:84%
for any human being to say,
and they are not, I am sorry.

00:56:24.550 --> 00:56:26.740 align:middle line:84%
Because anybody who's
married knows "I'm sorry"

00:56:26.740 --> 00:56:28.450 align:middle line:90%
has a lot of latitude, right?

00:56:28.450 --> 00:56:30.700 align:middle line:90%
I'm sorry you feel that I this.

00:56:30.700 --> 00:56:32.920 align:middle line:90%
I'm sorry you think I that.

00:56:32.920 --> 00:56:35.230 align:middle line:84%
I'm sorry you thought
I meant whatever.

00:56:35.230 --> 00:56:38.500 align:middle line:90%
I'm sorry doesn't cut it.

00:56:38.500 --> 00:56:45.220 align:middle line:84%
Much more profound are the
three words I was wrong.

00:56:45.220 --> 00:56:47.000 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Oh, yeah,
that's powerful.

00:56:47.000 --> 00:56:48.100 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: I was wrong.

00:56:48.100 --> 00:56:51.850 align:middle line:84%
That is a much higher
degree of culpability.

00:56:51.850 --> 00:56:54.850 align:middle line:84%
It takes the sting
out right away.

00:56:54.850 --> 00:56:56.200 align:middle line:90%
I was wrong.

00:56:56.200 --> 00:56:57.780 align:middle line:90%
There's no excuse.

00:56:57.780 --> 00:56:59.590 align:middle line:90%
There's no explanation.

00:56:59.590 --> 00:57:02.500 align:middle line:90%
I accept that I was wrong.

00:57:02.500 --> 00:57:04.960 align:middle line:90%
That starts the conversation.

00:57:04.960 --> 00:57:08.170 align:middle line:84%
Then, in the book, I talk
about a four-step process

00:57:08.170 --> 00:57:12.730 align:middle line:84%
that people can go through
to heal a relationship when

00:57:12.730 --> 00:57:15.610 align:middle line:84%
they have caused the
pain or caused the break.

00:57:15.610 --> 00:57:17.650 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Good.

00:57:17.650 --> 00:57:19.600 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: First step-- stop.

00:57:19.600 --> 00:57:22.240 align:middle line:84%
Whatever it is you were doing
that caused the problem--

00:57:22.240 --> 00:57:23.380 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: If you're
still doing it, yeah.

00:57:23.380 --> 00:57:23.500 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: --stop.

00:57:23.500 --> 00:57:25.580 align:middle line:84%
If you were texting and
driving and hit this poor guy

00:57:25.580 --> 00:57:27.080 align:middle line:84%
in the crosswalk
and killed him, you

00:57:27.080 --> 00:57:29.080 align:middle line:84%
lock that phone in
the glove compartment.

00:57:29.080 --> 00:57:31.330 align:middle line:90%
Stop whatever it is.

00:57:31.330 --> 00:57:34.390 align:middle line:84%
Drinking, opioid,
whatever it is, stop.

00:57:34.390 --> 00:57:36.710 align:middle line:90%
Gossip, stop.

00:57:36.710 --> 00:57:41.960 align:middle line:84%
Number two, confess
the sin out loud.

00:57:41.960 --> 00:57:43.570 align:middle line:90%
Say it out loud.

00:57:43.570 --> 00:57:45.305 align:middle line:84%
Saying to oneself,
oh, I feel awful.

00:57:45.305 --> 00:57:46.430 align:middle line:90%
I shouldn't have done that.

00:57:46.430 --> 00:57:47.260 align:middle line:90%
That was a mistake.

00:57:47.260 --> 00:57:54.190 align:middle line:84%
That's very different than
saying, Lisa, I was wrong.

00:57:54.190 --> 00:57:56.110 align:middle line:90%
I shouldn't have done that.

00:57:56.110 --> 00:57:57.970 align:middle line:90%
I'm really sorry.

00:57:57.970 --> 00:57:59.810 align:middle line:90%
I'm an alcoholic.

00:57:59.810 --> 00:58:00.820 align:middle line:90%
I need help.

00:58:00.820 --> 00:58:01.653 align:middle line:90%
Saying it out loud--

00:58:01.653 --> 00:58:02.903 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Is the accountability.

00:58:02.903 --> 00:58:04.060 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: --is to own it.

00:58:04.060 --> 00:58:05.440 align:middle line:90%
Stop.

00:58:05.440 --> 00:58:08.350 align:middle line:90%
Say it out loud.

00:58:08.350 --> 00:58:12.087 align:middle line:84%
Number three, ask
for forgiveness.

00:58:12.087 --> 00:58:13.920 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Yes, that's
what I was going to say.

00:58:13.920 --> 00:58:14.830 align:middle line:90%
Please.

00:58:14.830 --> 00:58:15.760 align:middle line:90%
I'm sorry.

00:58:15.760 --> 00:58:17.920 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: I was wrong.

00:58:17.920 --> 00:58:20.350 align:middle line:90%
I have this problem.

00:58:20.350 --> 00:58:22.150 align:middle line:90%
Please forgive me.

00:58:22.150 --> 00:58:26.470 align:middle line:84%
And finally, create
a system, scaffolding

00:58:26.470 --> 00:58:28.810 align:middle line:84%
in your life, that
will prevent you

00:58:28.810 --> 00:58:33.250 align:middle line:84%
from doing whatever it was
again if given the opportunity.

00:58:33.250 --> 00:58:35.685 align:middle line:84%
If you're an alcoholic,
never go into a bar.

00:58:35.685 --> 00:58:37.310 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Have an
accountability partner.

00:58:37.310 --> 00:58:40.090 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: If you're a sex
addict, no internet service

00:58:40.090 --> 00:58:41.770 align:middle line:84%
at your house, and
your cell phone

00:58:41.770 --> 00:58:43.540 align:middle line:84%
is only for phone
calls, whatever it is.

00:58:43.540 --> 00:58:48.370 align:middle line:84%
Create the scaffolding
you need to make sure

00:58:48.370 --> 00:58:50.380 align:middle line:90%
that this won't happen again.

00:58:50.380 --> 00:58:53.680 align:middle line:84%
Now, if you go through
all four of those steps

00:58:53.680 --> 00:58:56.260 align:middle line:84%
and you seek forgiveness
and the person

00:58:56.260 --> 00:58:57.760 align:middle line:90%
is unwilling to forgive--

00:58:57.760 --> 00:58:59.320 align:middle line:84%
now, this comes
from the Talmud--

00:58:59.320 --> 00:59:01.720 align:middle line:84%
three times, the sin
is then on that person.

00:59:01.720 --> 00:59:02.520 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Wow.

00:59:02.520 --> 00:59:04.420 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: Because you've
done everything you can.

00:59:04.420 --> 00:59:04.840 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Really?

00:59:04.840 --> 00:59:05.530 align:middle line:90%
Three times?

00:59:05.530 --> 00:59:06.330 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: Yes.

00:59:06.330 --> 00:59:08.750 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: No matter how
heinous the crime?

00:59:08.750 --> 00:59:09.550 align:middle line:90%
No?

00:59:09.550 --> 00:59:11.050 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: Well, there
are certain crimes,

00:59:11.050 --> 00:59:12.640 align:middle line:84%
like murder, which
are unforgivable,

00:59:12.640 --> 00:59:15.340 align:middle line:84%
because the person
can't forgive you.

00:59:15.340 --> 00:59:17.710 align:middle line:84%
But I would say if
the repentance is

00:59:17.710 --> 00:59:23.620 align:middle line:84%
sincere and lasting and
forgiveness is not forthcoming,

00:59:23.620 --> 00:59:26.740 align:middle line:84%
then you're choosing to
remain an unforgiving person.

00:59:26.740 --> 00:59:28.000 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Which is a choice.

00:59:28.000 --> 00:59:29.283 align:middle line:90%
Which is a choice, yes.

00:59:29.283 --> 00:59:30.700 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: And by
the way, forgiving

00:59:30.700 --> 00:59:32.440 align:middle line:90%
doesn't mean forgetting.

00:59:32.440 --> 00:59:34.638 align:middle line:90%
They're not the same thing.

00:59:34.638 --> 00:59:36.430 align:middle line:84%
I'm not asking you to
forget what happened.

00:59:36.430 --> 00:59:38.020 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: It's a
broad topic there.

00:59:38.020 --> 00:59:39.640 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: We could spend
another hour on that.

00:59:39.640 --> 00:59:40.440 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes.

00:59:40.440 --> 00:59:43.540 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: But I would
say that the book has

00:59:43.540 --> 00:59:45.230 align:middle line:90%
proven very helpful.

00:59:45.230 --> 00:59:48.010 align:middle line:84%
Many people have written
to me who have committed

00:59:48.010 --> 00:59:49.730 align:middle line:90%
financial crimes, for example--

00:59:49.730 --> 00:59:50.530 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Gambling.

00:59:50.530 --> 00:59:55.210 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: --who have committed
adultery of some form.

00:59:55.210 --> 00:59:57.790 align:middle line:84%
And it has helped
them make things

00:59:57.790 --> 01:00:02.380 align:middle line:84%
right with people they
love and care about.

01:00:02.380 --> 01:00:04.660 align:middle line:90%
Saying, I was wrong--

01:00:04.660 --> 01:00:06.150 align:middle line:90%
very powerful.

01:00:06.150 --> 01:00:07.660 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Yeah, it's
very powerful.

01:00:07.660 --> 01:00:11.718 align:middle line:84%
Asking for forgiveness,
stopping the repeated pattern,

01:00:11.718 --> 01:00:13.510 align:middle line:84%
those are things that
I would want to hear.

01:00:13.510 --> 01:00:15.010 align:middle line:84%
But you hear
stories all the time

01:00:15.010 --> 01:00:18.430 align:middle line:84%
of a person whose
child was killed

01:00:18.430 --> 01:00:22.510 align:middle line:84%
and they forgave the person
who was the shooter because

01:00:22.510 --> 01:00:25.510 align:middle line:84%
of the conversation that
it inspired and helped

01:00:25.510 --> 01:00:27.010 align:middle line:90%
so many people around.

01:00:27.010 --> 01:00:30.720 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: You know, I have to
say that this is an area where

01:00:30.720 --> 01:00:34.570 align:middle line:90%
I have a problem with that.

01:00:34.570 --> 01:00:37.800 align:middle line:84%
I can't judge why one person
chooses to forgive and why one

01:00:37.800 --> 01:00:38.600 align:middle line:90%
doesn't.

01:00:38.600 --> 01:00:41.380 align:middle line:84%
But I would say without a person
having gone through these four

01:00:41.380 --> 01:00:44.140 align:middle line:84%
steps, I don't think
they merit forgiveness.

01:00:44.140 --> 01:00:44.940 align:middle line:90%
I really don't.

01:00:44.940 --> 01:00:45.460 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: That's good to know.

01:00:45.460 --> 01:00:47.585 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: I don't think
forgiveness should be cheap.

01:00:47.585 --> 01:00:50.660 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Oh, no, not at all.

01:00:50.660 --> 01:00:51.710 align:middle line:90%
I agree.

01:00:51.710 --> 01:00:53.460 align:middle line:84%
It's a very, very huge
piece of awareness.

01:00:53.460 --> 01:00:57.380 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: If it's cheap, then the
person who committed this act

01:00:57.380 --> 01:01:00.810 align:middle line:84%
is not changing his or her
life as a result of it.

01:01:00.810 --> 01:01:03.650 align:middle line:84%
They're not hearing the
message of this book, which

01:01:03.650 --> 01:01:08.930 align:middle line:84%
is to come out of hell more
beautiful, a different person,

01:01:08.930 --> 01:01:11.060 align:middle line:84%
a stronger person,
a better person.

01:01:11.060 --> 01:01:14.210 align:middle line:84%
If forgiveness is
cheap, the perpetrator

01:01:14.210 --> 01:01:16.280 align:middle line:84%
is not going to come
out a better person.

01:01:16.280 --> 01:01:18.950 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Yes, absolutely,
and I agree with you.

01:01:18.950 --> 01:01:22.730 align:middle line:84%
And usually, the person that's
creating that level of pain

01:01:22.730 --> 01:01:26.280 align:middle line:84%
with somebody isn't the most
conscious in their actions.

01:01:26.280 --> 01:01:28.970 align:middle line:84%
So how do you get this
information to them?

01:01:28.970 --> 01:01:30.530 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: Well,
they may never be,

01:01:30.530 --> 01:01:32.600 align:middle line:84%
and they may, therefore,
never merit forgiveness.

01:01:32.600 --> 01:01:33.230 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right.

01:01:33.230 --> 01:01:34.030 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:01:34.030 --> 01:01:35.570 align:middle line:84%
So they live with
that, and they're

01:01:35.570 --> 01:01:37.010 align:middle line:84%
conscious or
unconscious about it?

01:01:37.010 --> 01:01:38.390 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: That's right.

01:01:38.390 --> 01:01:41.030 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Let's talk a little
bit about the idea of religion,

01:01:41.030 --> 01:01:43.340 align:middle line:84%
if we can for a
minute, and how--

01:01:43.340 --> 01:01:46.340 align:middle line:84%
do you feel that it
needs to modernize

01:01:46.340 --> 01:01:48.430 align:middle line:84%
or that it needs to still
hold on to tradition,

01:01:48.430 --> 01:01:50.680 align:middle line:84%
but it needs to move
forward in the world?

01:01:50.680 --> 01:01:51.740 align:middle line:90%
What are your thoughts?

01:01:51.740 --> 01:01:53.032 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: It's a delicate dance.

01:01:53.032 --> 01:01:54.510 align:middle line:90%
The answer is both.

01:01:54.510 --> 01:01:56.120 align:middle line:90%
The answer is both.

01:01:56.120 --> 01:01:58.850 align:middle line:84%
Religion at its best
is rooted in the past

01:01:58.850 --> 01:02:01.290 align:middle line:90%
but oriented to the future.

01:02:01.290 --> 01:02:02.755 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: It's always
been the case.

01:02:02.755 --> 01:02:04.130 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: Well,
sometimes religion

01:02:04.130 --> 01:02:09.050 align:middle line:84%
is overly rooted in the
past and doesn't really

01:02:09.050 --> 01:02:11.510 align:middle line:90%
talk much about the future.

01:02:11.510 --> 01:02:12.830 align:middle line:90%
And the past is the past.

01:02:12.830 --> 01:02:15.740 align:middle line:84%
You know, someone once said, the
single thing most responsible

01:02:15.740 --> 01:02:18.238 align:middle line:84%
for the good old
days is a bad memory.

01:02:18.238 --> 01:02:20.030 align:middle line:84%
They weren't really so
good if you actually

01:02:20.030 --> 01:02:22.400 align:middle line:90%
lived through them.

01:02:22.400 --> 01:02:25.840 align:middle line:84%
But I think the thing, for
me, certainly about Judaism--

01:02:25.840 --> 01:02:30.320 align:middle line:84%
and from which, of course,
Christianity and Islam flow.

01:02:30.320 --> 01:02:32.600 align:middle line:84%
So I see Judaism as
kind of the mother

01:02:32.600 --> 01:02:37.130 align:middle line:84%
religion of all monotheistic
religions, which it is.

01:02:37.130 --> 01:02:42.680 align:middle line:84%
Judaism uses the stories of
our past, but only in as much

01:02:42.680 --> 01:02:45.140 align:middle line:84%
as they are
beneficial in creating

01:02:45.140 --> 01:02:47.180 align:middle line:90%
a different and better future.

01:02:47.180 --> 01:02:50.420 align:middle line:84%
All of Judaism is oriented
toward a time in the future we

01:02:50.420 --> 01:02:53.620 align:middle line:84%
call the Olam Ha-Ba,
the world to come--

01:02:53.620 --> 01:02:57.780 align:middle line:84%
a kind of everlasting utopian
existence in the world.

01:02:57.780 --> 01:02:58.580 align:middle line:90%
So Judaism--

01:02:58.580 --> 01:03:00.247 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: That would
be good for everyone.

01:03:00.247 --> 01:03:03.110 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: Yes, and Judaism is
definitional forward-facing.

01:03:03.110 --> 01:03:05.840 align:middle line:84%
But of course, using
these foundation

01:03:05.840 --> 01:03:08.840 align:middle line:84%
stories from the past
to inform our decisions

01:03:08.840 --> 01:03:11.160 align:middle line:90%
about the future going forward.

01:03:11.160 --> 01:03:16.460 align:middle line:84%
The Native Americans
have a beautiful concept

01:03:16.460 --> 01:03:17.815 align:middle line:90%
called seventh generation.

01:03:17.815 --> 01:03:18.690 align:middle line:90%
You might have heard.

01:03:18.690 --> 01:03:20.840 align:middle line:84%
There's a line of cleaning
products at Whole Foods

01:03:20.840 --> 01:03:22.190 align:middle line:90%
called Seventh Generation.

01:03:22.190 --> 01:03:25.300 align:middle line:84%
So that comes from the great
law of the Iroquois nation.

01:03:25.300 --> 01:03:28.670 align:middle line:84%
And in their sort of
Bible, let's call it,

01:03:28.670 --> 01:03:32.810 align:middle line:84%
for monotheistic purposes, they
say that every time the elders

01:03:32.810 --> 01:03:34.340 align:middle line:84%
make a decision
for the tribe, they

01:03:34.340 --> 01:03:37.040 align:middle line:84%
have to consider the
impact of that decision

01:03:37.040 --> 01:03:39.650 align:middle line:84%
on the seventh
generation to follow.

01:03:39.650 --> 01:03:42.990 align:middle line:84%
So it's a very forward-looking
decision-making process.

01:03:42.990 --> 01:03:45.800 align:middle line:84%
And I think religion,
at its best, is that.

01:03:45.800 --> 01:03:47.150 align:middle line:90%
I often put it to people--

01:03:47.150 --> 01:03:50.090 align:middle line:84%
I think to be a religious person
means that you are choosing

01:03:50.090 --> 01:03:53.300 align:middle line:90%
to live as a good ancestor.

01:03:53.300 --> 01:03:56.150 align:middle line:84%
Now, we don't think of
ourselves as ancestors.

01:03:56.150 --> 01:03:58.640 align:middle line:90%
We are, just not yet.

01:03:58.640 --> 01:04:00.680 align:middle line:84%
So our job is to
be good ancestors,

01:04:00.680 --> 01:04:03.890 align:middle line:84%
and that means to think about
the future more than the past.

01:04:03.890 --> 01:04:05.390 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: There are
religions, though,

01:04:05.390 --> 01:04:08.260 align:middle line:84%
that think that their
religion is the only way,

01:04:08.260 --> 01:04:10.370 align:middle line:84%
and that other religions
would say that they're

01:04:10.370 --> 01:04:12.360 align:middle line:90%
the basis of all religion.

01:04:12.360 --> 01:04:13.160 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: Yeah.

01:04:13.160 --> 01:04:16.070 align:middle line:84%
There's more than
one path, of course.

01:04:16.070 --> 01:04:18.290 align:middle line:84%
And you know, Judaism
is my religion.

01:04:18.290 --> 01:04:19.880 align:middle line:90%
It's my love.

01:04:19.880 --> 01:04:21.140 align:middle line:90%
I love my wife.

01:04:21.140 --> 01:04:23.070 align:middle line:84%
We got engaged on
our second date.

01:04:23.070 --> 01:04:25.020 align:middle line:90%
We've been married 33 years.

01:04:25.020 --> 01:04:25.820 align:middle line:90%
I love her.

01:04:25.820 --> 01:04:32.520 align:middle line:84%
Does that mean that someone
loves his wife any less?

01:04:32.520 --> 01:04:33.320 align:middle line:90%
No.

01:04:33.320 --> 01:04:35.840 align:middle line:84%
But this is my wife,
and that's your wife.

01:04:35.840 --> 01:04:36.920 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Great example.

01:04:36.920 --> 01:04:38.180 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: Love isn't limited.

01:04:38.180 --> 01:04:39.080 align:middle line:90%
It's limitless.

01:04:39.080 --> 01:04:45.620 align:middle line:84%
And so I think all true
religions are a path of love,

01:04:45.620 --> 01:04:49.460 align:middle line:84%
and they're of equal beauty,
but they're different.

01:04:49.460 --> 01:04:51.560 align:middle line:84%
We sometimes think
differences are bad.

01:04:51.560 --> 01:04:52.730 align:middle line:90%
I don't see things that way.

01:04:52.730 --> 01:04:54.830 align:middle line:84%
I think differences
are beautiful.

01:04:54.830 --> 01:04:57.170 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Well, you have a
love, also, of rock and roll,

01:04:57.170 --> 01:04:57.970 align:middle line:90%
apparently.

01:04:57.970 --> 01:04:59.830 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: Yeah, I knew
we'd get to that.

01:04:59.830 --> 01:05:02.710 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: This beautiful
Rock and Roll Hall of Fame

01:05:02.710 --> 01:05:04.160 align:middle line:90%
is in your office, fun fact.

01:05:04.160 --> 01:05:06.590 align:middle line:90%
Take a look here at this video.

01:05:06.590 --> 01:05:09.020 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: My rock and
roll photography wall

01:05:09.020 --> 01:05:14.540 align:middle line:84%
at my office in the Irmas campus
really started 18 years ago

01:05:14.540 --> 01:05:17.270 align:middle line:90%
on my 40th birthday.

01:05:17.270 --> 01:05:20.440 align:middle line:84%
And I happened to
be in New York,

01:05:20.440 --> 01:05:21.930 align:middle line:90%
walking around the village.

01:05:21.930 --> 01:05:24.520 align:middle line:84%
And I walked into a rock and
roll photography gallery.

01:05:24.520 --> 01:05:25.690 align:middle line:90%
[BELL JINGLING]

01:05:25.690 --> 01:05:32.200 align:middle line:84%
And there was an amazing shot
of Bob Dylan there from 1965.

01:05:32.200 --> 01:05:33.790 align:middle line:90%
And it's this great shot of him.

01:05:33.790 --> 01:05:36.220 align:middle line:84%
He's half in shadow,
half in light,

01:05:36.220 --> 01:05:39.310 align:middle line:84%
but he has a kind of
disinterested look on his face.

01:05:39.310 --> 01:05:41.180 align:middle line:84%
And the best thing
about this photograph

01:05:41.180 --> 01:05:43.180 align:middle line:84%
is if you look really
carefully-- now, remember,

01:05:43.180 --> 01:05:45.135 align:middle line:84%
he's a big star
already at this point.

01:05:45.135 --> 01:05:46.510 align:middle line:10%
If you look really
carefully, you

01:05:46.510 --> 01:05:50.080 align:middle line:10%
can see here a safety pin
holding his sunglasses

01:05:50.080 --> 01:05:51.430 align:middle line:10%
together, which I just love.

01:05:51.430 --> 01:05:53.660 align:middle line:84%
That's pure Minnesota
right there.

01:05:53.660 --> 01:05:55.240 align:middle line:90%
It's just pure pragmatism.

01:05:55.240 --> 01:05:56.680 align:middle line:90%
I love music.

01:05:56.680 --> 01:05:57.850 align:middle line:90%
I love rock and roll.

01:05:57.850 --> 01:06:00.180 align:middle line:90%
I love lyrics.

01:06:00.180 --> 01:06:03.670 align:middle line:84%
And I'm a huge Bob Dylan
fan, because his lyrics

01:06:03.670 --> 01:06:05.304 align:middle line:90%
were very important to me.

01:06:05.304 --> 01:06:08.148 align:middle line:84%
[MUSIC - BOB DYLAN, "GIRL FROM
 NORTH COUNTRY"]

01:06:08.148 --> 01:06:12.830 align:middle line:84%
>>BOB DYLAN: (SINGING) In
the brightness of my day.

01:06:12.830 --> 01:06:16.190 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: And this, this is
Dylan and George Harrison

01:06:16.190 --> 01:06:19.180 align:middle line:84%
at the Concert for Bangladesh,
which was really the first rock

01:06:19.180 --> 01:06:20.720 align:middle line:90%
and roll benefit concert.

01:06:20.720 --> 01:06:22.340 align:middle line:84%
And this was the
first time, I think,

01:06:22.340 --> 01:06:24.900 align:middle line:84%
that Dylan played in public
after his motorcycle accident.

01:06:24.900 --> 01:06:26.480 align:middle line:90%
He played three songs.

01:06:26.480 --> 01:06:29.710 align:middle line:84%
I tried to get as many
California shots as I can.

01:06:29.710 --> 01:06:34.340 align:middle line:84%
So this is Neil Young on
the beach in Malibu in 1975

01:06:34.340 --> 01:06:35.630 align:middle line:90%
by Henry Diltz.

01:06:35.630 --> 01:06:36.950 align:middle line:90%
And this is by Baron Wolman.

01:06:36.950 --> 01:06:39.290 align:middle line:10%
That's Frank Zappa
on a bulldozer

01:06:39.290 --> 01:06:44.240 align:middle line:10%
on Laurel Canyon in 1968,
which I think is just

01:06:44.240 --> 01:06:48.110 align:middle line:10%
a fantastic, fantastic shot.

01:06:48.110 --> 01:06:50.300 align:middle line:84%
Love this shot of John
and Yoko, of course,

01:06:50.300 --> 01:06:52.070 align:middle line:90%
and all they represent.

01:06:52.070 --> 01:06:55.430 align:middle line:84%
Many people who come to
visit me in that office

01:06:55.430 --> 01:06:59.090 align:middle line:84%
have either never been
to visit a rabbi before

01:06:59.090 --> 01:07:01.177 align:middle line:84%
or had a bad experience
visiting a rabbi before.

01:07:01.177 --> 01:07:02.760 align:middle line:84%
And they have all
these preconceptions

01:07:02.760 --> 01:07:04.470 align:middle line:84%
that the rabbi's
going to be boring,

01:07:04.470 --> 01:07:07.030 align:middle line:84%
the rabbi's going to be old
and stuffy, the rabbi's going

01:07:07.030 --> 01:07:09.590 align:middle line:90%
to be distant, whatever it is.

01:07:09.590 --> 01:07:15.830 align:middle line:84%
And I can actually physically
see people becoming disarmed

01:07:15.830 --> 01:07:17.540 align:middle line:84%
when they walk into
that office and look

01:07:17.540 --> 01:07:20.150 align:middle line:84%
at the wall with all
those photographs on it.

01:07:20.150 --> 01:07:22.280 align:middle line:90%
I can see them literally.

01:07:22.280 --> 01:07:25.130 align:middle line:84%
Relax I can see them
thinking to themselves,

01:07:25.130 --> 01:07:26.570 align:middle line:90%
this might not be so bad.

01:07:26.570 --> 01:07:29.180 align:middle line:84%
This guy might be
kind of normal.

01:07:29.180 --> 01:07:33.230 align:middle line:84%
And that's another reason why I
have that artwork in my office.

01:07:33.230 --> 01:07:38.150 align:middle line:84%
It's a way of opening people
up before they even sit down

01:07:38.150 --> 01:07:40.940 align:middle line:84%
on the couch and get
ready to discuss with me

01:07:40.940 --> 01:07:44.387 align:middle line:84%
whatever it is they've
come to see me about.

01:07:44.387 --> 01:07:45.220 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: I love that.

01:07:45.220 --> 01:07:47.618 align:middle line:84%
It's another way of
breaking down barriers and--

01:07:47.618 --> 01:07:48.910 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: It's very intentional.

01:07:48.910 --> 01:07:50.243 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: --yeah, letting people--

01:07:50.243 --> 01:07:53.020 align:middle line:84%
so I love to ask my guests,
what is the biggest why?

01:07:53.020 --> 01:07:57.370 align:middle line:84%
What's the biggest reason you
do what you do as a rabbi,

01:07:57.370 --> 01:08:00.140 align:middle line:84%
as the senior rabbi
of the temple?

01:08:00.140 --> 01:08:00.940 align:middle line:90%
What is it?

01:08:00.940 --> 01:08:05.290 align:middle line:84%
>>LEDER: You know, since
I was a very young boy,

01:08:05.290 --> 01:08:08.360 align:middle line:84%
I have been drawn
to help people.

01:08:08.360 --> 01:08:09.940 align:middle line:84%
I remember in
fourth grade-- so I

01:08:09.940 --> 01:08:13.390 align:middle line:84%
think that's about 9 or 10
years old, 10 years old.

01:08:13.390 --> 01:08:15.940 align:middle line:10%
I remember in this
little elementary school

01:08:15.940 --> 01:08:19.960 align:middle line:10%
in suburban Minneapolis, there
was a girl in the class--

01:08:19.960 --> 01:08:21.040 align:middle line:10%
I won't mention her name.

01:08:21.040 --> 01:08:23.620 align:middle line:84%
There was a girl in the class
who, today, we would say

01:08:23.620 --> 01:08:26.380 align:middle line:90%
was on the spectrum.

01:08:26.380 --> 01:08:30.819 align:middle line:84%
You know, in 1970, we
didn't have that language.

01:08:30.819 --> 01:08:35.260 align:middle line:84%
And I remember fantasizing
about going to the teacher, Mrs.

01:08:35.260 --> 01:08:39.093 align:middle line:84%
Hollingsworth, and
saying, you know

01:08:39.093 --> 01:08:41.260 align:middle line:84%
would you just let me talk
to her for a few minutes?

01:08:41.260 --> 01:08:43.550 align:middle line:90%
I think I can help her.

01:08:43.550 --> 01:08:47.290 align:middle line:10%
Now, I didn't do it, but that
was my fantasy at 10 years old,

01:08:47.290 --> 01:08:50.859 align:middle line:10%
was that here's a person
who's clearly suffering.

01:08:50.859 --> 01:08:52.899 align:middle line:90%
I'd like to help.

01:08:52.899 --> 01:08:58.529 align:middle line:84%
And for as long as I can
remember, that's been my why.

01:08:58.529 --> 01:09:00.160 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: You never
did talk to her?

01:09:00.160 --> 01:09:01.000 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: No.

01:09:01.000 --> 01:09:01.800 align:middle line:90%
I wish I had.

01:09:01.800 --> 01:09:04.127 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: You've talked
to plenty others.

01:09:04.127 --> 01:09:04.960 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: I've tried.

01:09:04.960 --> 01:09:05.470 align:middle line:90%
I've tried my best.

01:09:05.470 --> 01:09:06.520 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: I think
you've made up for it.

01:09:06.520 --> 01:09:07.429 align:middle line:90%
Thank you so much--

01:09:07.429 --> 01:09:08.229 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: Thank you.

01:09:08.229 --> 01:09:11.290 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: --for showing us how
grief can truly transform us

01:09:11.290 --> 01:09:12.889 align:middle line:84%
and how suffering
can transform us.

01:09:12.889 --> 01:09:13.689 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: Thank you.

01:09:13.689 --> 01:09:15.790 align:middle line:84%
I'm very grateful for the
opportunity to speak with you.

01:09:15.790 --> 01:09:16.630 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Absolutely.

01:09:16.630 --> 01:09:17.350 align:middle line:90%
>>LEDER: Thank you.

01:09:17.350 --> 01:09:18.399 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And if you
would like to watch

01:09:18.399 --> 01:09:20.470 align:middle line:84%
more inspirational
programming, please check out

01:09:20.470 --> 01:09:22.180 align:middle line:90%
"Inspirations" on Gaia.

01:09:22.180 --> 01:09:24.410 align:middle line:10%
I'm Lisa Garr, and
until next time,

01:09:24.410 --> 01:09:27.369 align:middle line:10%
I invite you to stay aware.

